{"title_page": "Order of St. George (Habsburg-Lorraine)", "text_new": "{{about|the active order of chivalry|the historic order|Order of Saint George (House of Habsburg)|other uses|Order of St. George (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox order\n|title    = Imperial and Royal Order of Saint George\n|image    = File:Imperial Coat of Arms of the Empire of Austria.svg\n|caption  =\n|image2   = [[File:St._Georgs-Orden_(Habsburg-Lothringen).png|100px]]\n|caption2 = [[Ribbon]] of the order\n|awarded_by      =  The Head of the [[House of Habsburg]] \n|type        = [[Dynastic order]]\n|for         = \n|motto       = \n|date        = 30 April 2011\n|house       = [[House of Habsburg]]\n|religion    = [[Roman Catholic]]\n|ribbon=\n|head_title  = Sovereign\n|head        = [[Karl von Habsburg|Archduke Karl]]  [[File:Imperial Standard of Austria-Hungary (1915-1918).svg|30px]]\n|head2_title = Grand Master\n|head2       = [[Georg von Habsburg|Archduke Georg]]\n|head3_title = [[Chancellor]]\n|head3       =\n|notes       =\n|higher      = [[Order of the Golden Fleece]]\n}}\nThe '''Imperial and Royal Order of Saint George''' or simply '''Order of Saint George''' ({{lang-de|St. Georgs-Orden \u2013 Ein europ\u00e4ischer Orden des Hauses Habsburg-Lothringen}}<ref>{{cite web |title=St. Georgs-Orden Geschichte |url=https://www.georgsorden.at/geschichte/?L=1 |website=georgsorden.at |accessdate=18 November 2019}}</ref>) is a [[Dynastic order|dynastic]] [[order of chivalry]] and thus a house order of the [[House of Habsburg]], the former Imperial and Royal House of the [[Holy Roman Empire]], the [[Habsburg Monarchy]], the [[Austrian Empire|Empire of Austria]], the [[Austria-Hungary|Austro-Hungarian Monarchy]], the [[Kingdom of Hungary]], the Crown lands of Bohemia and Croatia and further nations.\n\nIt is a European and non-partisan order, which supports the transnational idea of [[Mitteleuropa]] ([[Habsburg Monarchy|Habsburg]] definition) and increased need for cooperation between the countries of [[Central Europe|Central]] and [[Southeastern Europe]]. It is committed to Christianity and a united self-confident Europe. It has approximately 600 knights and Commanderies in [[Austria]], [[Croatia]], [[Czech Republic]], [[Germany]], [[Hungary]], [[Italy]], [[Netherlands]], [[Serbia]], [[Slovenia]], [[Switzerland]] and the [[United Kingdom]]. The order has women and men as members.<ref name=\"ordensregierung\">{{cite web |title=Die Ordensregierung |url=https://www.georgsorden.at/struktur/die-ordensregierung/?L=1 |website=georgsorden.at |accessdate=14 June 2018}}</ref> \n\nThe order represents the centuries-old Habsburg principle of \"live and let live\" in relation to ethnic groups, peoples, minorities, religions, cultures and languages.<ref>For the ability of the Habsburg monarchy to protect and promote the diversity of its peoples and minorities, see: Pieter M. Judson \"The Habsburg Empire. A New History\" (Harvard University Press 2016).</ref><ref>For more information on these Habsburg principles, see in particular: Christopher Clark \"The Sleepwalkers\" (New York 2012).</ref> \n\nThe motto of the order is \"[[Viribus Unitis]]\".\n\n== Patron saint ==\nThe patron saint of the order is [[St. George]] as a symbol of chivalry.\n\n== Principle ==  \nThe order is non-profit and fights the eightfold misery like illness, abandonment, homelessness, hunger, lovelessness, guilt, indifference and unbelief. \n\nThe Order of St. George aims to worship St. George as the patron saint of chivalry, to cultivate chivalry and a chivalrous outlook on life.\n\n== History == \n[[File:Albrecht D\u00fcrer - Portrait of Maximilian I - Google Art Project.jpg|thumb|[[Maximilian I, Holy Roman Emperor |Emperor Maximilian of Habsburg]]]]\nThe origins of today's Order of St. George, a European order of the House of Habsburg-Lorraine, go back to 1308. [[Henry VII, Holy Roman Emperor|Emperor Henry VII]] donated the \"Order of the Old Nobility\" (or later \"Order of the Four Roman Emperors\"), which can be regarded as the predecessor of today's order. The \"Order of the Old Nobility\" developed differently over the centuries after its foundation and had experienced heyday and decline. \n[[File:Emperor karl of austria-hungary 1917.png|thumb|Blessed Emperor  [[Charles I of Austria]] , King of Hungary (as Charles IV, Hungarian: IV. K\u00e1roly), King of Bohemia.]]\nThe order also has traditional roots in the Austrian Order of St. George, which was founded by [[Frederick III, Holy Roman Emperor|Emperor Friedrich III. of Habsburg]] and [[Pope Paul II]] in Rome in 1469. The headquarters were the former Benedictine monastery Millstatt, the second headquarters was Wiener Neustadt. [[Maximilian I, Holy Roman Emperor |Emperor Maximilian of Habsburg]] was a particular patron of the order. It is believed that the Order of St. George by Emperor Friedrich III was connected to another previous order, the \"Austrian Dragon Society\" founded in 1409 in \u00d6denburg, which in turn was directly connected to the Order of the Dragon by the [[Sigismund, Holy Roman Emperor|Hungarian King and Emperor Sigismund]].\n\nThe sovereignty of the Order of St. George or the St. George Knights Brotherhood, which was also founded by Emperor Maximilian I, has remained with the House of Habsburg-Lorraine to this day. Emperor Maximilian I tried to promote his St. George's associations and use them politically. On November 15, 1494, for example, he made an appeal to all Christian kings and princes, as well as to all Christianity, to join the Brotherhood and to support a Turkish campaign planned by the emperor for the following year, but without finding much interest. He gave the knights who would take part in this campaign the privilege of wearing a crown in their coat of arms and thus created the status of the \"crowned knight\".<ref>Manfred Hollegger \"Maximilian I.\" (2005), p 150.</ref>\n\nEmpress [[Maria Theresa]] is said to have issued new statutes of the order in 1765.\n\n[[Franz Joseph I of Austria|Emperor Franz Joseph I]] confirmed the priory of the Order of St. George in Austria in 1848.\n\nIn 1917 [[Charles I of Austria|Emperor Charles I]] confirmed the order as a purely secular order of knights in the future.<ref>Roman Proch\u00e1zka \"\u00d6sterreichisches Ordenshandbuch\" (1979), p 274.</ref>  \n\nBetween 1919 and 1920 the order structures were modernized by persons approved by the emperor. Due to the situation in exile of the imperial family, the leadership of the order then went to [[Prince Johannes of Liechtenstein (1873\u20131959)|Prince Johannes of Liechtenstein]], although the title of protector and holder of the order remained with the House of Habsburg.\n\nThen there was a need to adapt the statutes of the order to modern conditions. On February 7, 1926, a constitutional reorganization council in Hanover issued a new order, whereby the nobility was no longer required for admission and the order was given the name \"Old St. George Knightly Order, also known as the Order of the Four Roman Emperors\". The order continued to claim that the unity and interests of the Central European peoples and nations were guaranteed for centuries by the Holy Roman Empire and the Habsburg monarchy.[[File:Oliver Mark - Otto Habsburg-Lothringen, P\u00f6cking 2006.jpg|thumb|Archduke [[Otto von Habsburg]]]]\n\nIn 1935, due to the political situation in the German Reich, the seat of the order was moved to Salzburg, from where he stood up against National Socialism, for [[Central Europe]] independent of Nazi Germany and for the re-establishment of the House of Habsburg. In 1938, after the annexation of Austria, the order was banned and dissolved by the Nazis for political reasons.<ref>Johannes Krejci \"Aus der Geschichte des Alten Ordens vom St. Georg.\", Wien 2002.</ref> Many who campaigned for Habsburg during the Nazi era were killed, taken to a concentration camp, or persecuted by the Gestapo.<ref>Elisabeth Boeckl-Klamper, Thomas Mang, Wolfgang Neugebauer \"Gestapo-Leitstelle Wien 1938\u20131945.\" Vienna 2018, p 299\u2013305.</ref><ref>Hans Schafranek \"Widerstand und Verrat: Gestapospitzel im antifaschistischen Untergrund.\" Vienna 2017, p 161\u2013248.</ref> The House of Habsburg was an early supporter of European integration and a vehement opponent of [[National Socialism]] and [[Communism]].<ref>Timothy Snyder \"The Red Prince: The Secret Lives of a Habsburg Archduke\" (2008); James Longo \"Hitler and the Habsburgs: The Fuhrer's Vendetta Against the Austrian Royals\" (2018).</ref>\n\nDuring communism, former members of the order or other Habsburg supporters were persecuted behind the [[Iron Curtain]] because the communist regimes feared opposition in their oppressed countries.\n\nThe cancellation of the \"Old Order of St. George\" (also called \"Order of the Four Roman Emperors\") by Nazi Germany in 1935/1938 was reversed by the reorganization convention on January 18, 2008. Because after the fall of the Iron Curtain and due to the complete independence of the new Central European countries from the USSR, there was now the possibility and need to reactivate communities in order to connect the peoples in this area. Archduke [[Otto von Habsburg]], Archduke [[Karl von Habsburg]] and  [[Vincenz Liechtenstein|Prince Vincenz of Liechtenstein]] were significantly involved.\n\nAt the convent on April 30, 2011, Archduke Karl von Habsburg confirmed the \u201cSt. Order of George - A European order of the House of Habsburg-Lorraine\" as an order of the [[House of Habsburg]]. Building on the centuries-old Habsburg motto \" [[Viribus Unitis]]\", the peoples and nations of Central Europe should now take care of their interests together. In the framework of this European Habsburg Order, the historical connections are to be strengthened and expanded, also in order to be able to perform better in United Europe. The Order sees it as its task to recognize and preserve the common cultural, scientific and interpersonal heritage of Central Europe.<ref>Regarding the Habsburg tradition in this regard: Moritz Csaky \"Pluralit\u00e9 culturelle et identit\u00e9: Criteres d\u00b4 une auto-reconnaissance transnationale sous la Monarchie des Habsbourg\" Les Temps Modernes 48:550 (1992), p 154.</ref> The model is the tolerant Habsburg approach to the national diversity of the peoples of Central Europe.<ref>Paul Miller-Melamed and Claire Morelon \"What the Hapsburg Empire Got Right\" in New York Times, 10 September 2019.</ref><ref>Johannes Feichtinger, Gary B. Cohen \"Understanding multiculturalism: The Habsburg central European experience\" (2014).</ref><ref>William M. Johnston, \"The Political and Cultural Background of Vienna 1900: A Golden Age of Cultural Exchange\" (Melbourne 2011).</ref>\n\nThe members of the order should also use those Habsburg roots that extend beyond Central Europe, for example to Italy, Switzerland, Spain, France, Great Britain, Germany, the Benelux countries and the Orient. Accordingly, the \u201cSt. Order of George - A European order of the House of Habsburg-Lorraine\" has a close relationship with the \"Austrian pilgrim hospice for the Holy Family\" in Jerusalem, which was donated by Emperor Franz Joseph I for all people of the Habsburg monarchy.<ref>[https://www.austrianhospice.com/ Austrian Pilgrim Hospice to the Holy Family in Jerusalem]</ref>\n\nRegarding the necessary moral attitude of a St. Georg knight today, Bishop Klaus K\u00fcng said during an investiture in Budapest: \"When it comes to values \u200b\u200bthat are of great importance to human development, it is necessary to stand up for them courageously. What are these values? - Ultimately, it's Christian values.\" But that also means that the order in Habsburg tradition is particularly dedicated to the peaceful balance between religions and the intercultural encounter between [[Christianity]], [[Judaism]]<ref>The House of Habsburg already vehemently opposed anti-Semitism in the 19th century. For example, Emperor Franz Joseph I said: Anti-Semitism should be exterminated. See in detail: Robert S. Wistrich \"Die Juden Wiens im Zeitalter Kaiser Franz Josephs - The Jews of Vienna in the Age of Franz Joseph\" (Oxford 1994), p 149.</ref> and [[Islam]]<ref>As early as 1912 (- through the annexation of Bosnia and Herzegovina under state law in 1908, 600,000 Muslims belonged to the k.u.k. Monarchy) was the guarantee of free and public religious practice of the Muslims regulated in the Habsburg monarchy. Bosnian Muslims got the highest Awards for bravery and loyalty and provided the bodyguard of the emperor. [http://www.bundesheer.at/pdf_pool/publikationen/ms_23_5.pdf European military pastoral care between Christianity, Islam and secularization - Austrian Armed Forces]</ref>.<ref>On Habsburg and the diversity of religions: Pieter M. Judson \"The Habsburg Empire. A New History\" (Harvard 2016).</ref>\n\nIn addition to local meetings, the order has major events such as in Vienna, Budapest, Prague, Zagreb, Ljubljana, Trieste, Milan, London, Frankfurt, Salzburg and Tyrol.\n\nThe admission was and is a special privilege and a great honor.\n[[File:Insignie des St. Georgs-Orden (Habsburg-Lothringen).png|thumb|Insignia of the Order of St. George]]\n\n== Notable members ==\n{{div col|colwidth=18em}}\n*{{flagicon|AUT}} [[Duchess Eilika of Oldenburg|Archduchess Eilika]]<ref name=\"ordensregierung\"/>\n*{{flagicon|NLD}} [[Jan Peter Balkenende]]\n*{{flagicon|SVK}} [[J\u00e1n \u010carnogursk\u00fd]]\n*{{flagicon|ITA}} [[Luis Durnwalder]]\n*{{flagicon|ITA}} [[Massimiliano Fedriga]]\n*{{flagicon|AUT}} [[Norbert Hofer]]\n*{{flagicon|MKD}} [[Gjorge Ivanov]]\n*{{flagicon|AUT}} [[Karlheinz Kopf]]\n*{{flagicon|GBR}} [[David Mackintosh (politician)|David Mackintosh]]\n*{{flagicon|ITA}} [[Roberto Maroni]]\n*{{flagicon|AUT}} [[Siegfried Nagl]]\n*{{flagicon|AUT}} [[Harald Ofner]]\n*{{flagicon|BUL}} [[Rosen Plevneliev]]\n*{{flagicon|AUT}} [[Erwin Pr\u00f6ll]]\n*{{flagicon|AUT}} [[Josef P\u00fchringer]]\n*{{flagicon|GBR}} [[George Robertson, Baron Robertson of Port Ellen|Baron Robertson of Port Ellen]]\n*{{flagicon|ITA}} [[Luigi Roth]]\n*{{flagicon|AUT}} [[Franz Schausberger]]\n*{{flagicon|GER}} [[Peter Schmitz]]\n*{{flagicon|HUN}} [[Zsolt Semj\u00e9n]]\n*{{flagicon|AUT}} [[Herwig van Staa]]\n*{{flagicon|GBR}} [[David Steel|Lord Steel of Aikwood]]\n*{{flagicon|AUT}} [[Ursula Stenzel]]\n*{{flagicon|SLO}} [[Verica Trstenjak]]\n*{{flagicon|GBR}} [[Alan Watson, Baron Watson of Richmond|Baron Watson of Richmond]]\n{{div col end}}\n<small>Source: [https://www.georgsorden.at/struktur/die-ordensregierung/ Ehrenritter]</small>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://www.karlvonhabsburg.at/organisationen/sankt-georgs-orden/ History of the former National Order and the current Chartered Dynastic Order]\n*[https://www.georgsorden.at/ Official website]\n*[https://www.facebook.com/georgsorden Facebook Page]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Order of St. George}}\n[[Category:Orders of chivalry of Austria]]\n[[Category:House of Habsburg]]\n\n{{Austria-org-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{about|the active order of chivalry|the historic order|Order of Saint George (House of Habsburg)|other uses|Order of St. George (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox order\n|title    = Imperial and Royal Order of Saint George\n|image    = File:Imperial Coat of Arms of the Empire of Austria.svg\n|caption  =\n|image2   = [[File:St._Georgs-Orden_(Habsburg-Lothringen).png|100px]]\n|caption2 = [[Ribbon]] of the order\n|awarded_by      =  The Head of the [[House of Habsburg]] \n|type        = [[Dynastic order]]\n|for         = \n|motto       = \n|date        = 30 April 2011\n|house       = [[House of Habsburg]]\n|religion    = [[Roman Catholic]]\n|ribbon=\n|head_title  = Sovereign\n|head        = [[Karl von Habsburg|Archduke Karl]]  [[File:Imperial Standard of Austria-Hungary (1915-1918).svg|30px]]\n|head2_title = Grand Master\n|head2       = [[Georg von Habsburg|Archduke Georg]]\n|head3_title = [[Chancellor]]\n|head3       =\n|notes       =\n|higher      = [[Order of the Golden Fleece]]\n}}\nThe '''Imperial and Royal Order of Saint George''' or simply '''Order of Saint George''' ({{lang-de|St. Georgs-Orden \u2013 Ein europ\u00e4ischer Orden des Hauses Habsburg-Lothringen}}<ref>{{cite web |title=St. Georgs-Orden Geschichte |url=https://www.georgsorden.at/geschichte/?L=1 |website=georgsorden.at |accessdate=18 November 2019}}</ref>) is a [[Dynastic order|dynastic]] [[order of chivalry]] and thus a house order of the [[House of Habsburg]], the former Imperial and Royal House of the [[Holy Roman Empire]], the [[Habsburg Monarchy]], the [[Austrian Empire|Empire of Austria]], the [[Austria-Hungary|Austro-Hungarian Monarchy]], the [[Kingdom of Hungary]], the Crown lands of Bohemia and Croatia and further nations.\n\nIt is an European and non-partisan order, which supports the transnational idea of [[Mitteleuropa]] ([[Habsburg Monarchy|Habsburg]] definition) and increased need for cooperation between the countries of [[Central Europe|Central]] and [[Southeastern Europe]]. It is committed to Christianity and a united self-confident Europe. It has approximately 600 knights and Commanderies in [[Austria]], [[Croatia]], [[Czech Republic]], [[Germany]], [[Hungary]], [[Italy]], [[Netherlands]], [[Serbia]], [[Slovenia]], [[Switzerland]] and the [[United Kingdom]]. The order has women and men as members.<ref name=\"ordensregierung\">{{cite web |title=Die Ordensregierung |url=https://www.georgsorden.at/struktur/die-ordensregierung/?L=1 |website=georgsorden.at |accessdate=14 June 2018}}</ref> \n\nThe order represents the centuries-old Habsburg principle of \"live and let live\" in relation to ethnic groups, peoples, minorities, religions, cultures and languages.<ref>For the ability of the Habsburg monarchy to protect and promote the diversity of its peoples and minorities, see: Pieter M. Judson \"The Habsburg Empire. A New History\" (Harvard University Press 2016).</ref><ref>For more information on these Habsburg principles, see in particular: Christopher Clark \"The Sleepwalkers\" (New York 2012).</ref> \n\nThe motto of the order is \"[[Viribus Unitis]]\".\n\n== Patron saint ==\nThe patron saint of the order is [[St. George]] as a symbol of chivalry.\n\n== Principle ==  \nThe order is non-profit and fights the eightfold misery like illness, abandonment, homelessness, hunger, lovelessness, guilt, indifference and unbelief. \n\nThe Order of St. George aims to worship St. George as the patron saint of chivalry, to cultivate chivalry and a chivalrous outlook on life.\n\n== History == \n[[File:Albrecht D\u00fcrer - Portrait of Maximilian I - Google Art Project.jpg|thumb|[[Maximilian I, Holy Roman Emperor |Emperor Maximilian of Habsburg]]]]\nThe origins of today's Order of St. George, a European order of the House of Habsburg-Lorraine, go back to 1308. [[Henry VII, Holy Roman Emperor|Emperor Henry VII]] donated the \"Order of the Old Nobility\" (or later \"Order of the Four Roman Emperors\"), which can be regarded as the predecessor of today's order. The \"Order of the Old Nobility\" developed differently over the centuries after its foundation and had experienced heyday and decline. \n[[File:Emperor karl of austria-hungary 1917.png|thumb|Blessed Emperor  [[Charles I of Austria]] , King of Hungary (as Charles IV, Hungarian: IV. K\u00e1roly), King of Bohemia.]]\nThe order also has traditional roots in the Austrian Order of St. George, which was founded by [[Frederick III, Holy Roman Emperor|Emperor Friedrich III. of Habsburg]] and [[Pope Paul II]] in Rome in 1469. The headquarters were the former Benedictine monastery Millstatt, the second headquarters was Wiener Neustadt. [[Maximilian I, Holy Roman Emperor |Emperor Maximilian of Habsburg]] was a particular patron of the order. It is believed that the Order of St. George by Emperor Friedrich III was connected to another previous order, the \"Austrian Dragon Society\" founded in 1409 in \u00d6denburg, which in turn was directly connected to the Order of the Dragon by the [[Sigismund, Holy Roman Emperor|Hungarian King and Emperor Sigismund]].\n\nThe sovereignty of the Order of St. George or the St. George Knights Brotherhood, which was also founded by Emperor Maximilian I, has remained with the House of Habsburg-Lorraine to this day. Emperor Maximilian I tried to promote his St. George's associations and use them politically. On November 15, 1494, for example, he made an appeal to all Christian kings and princes, as well as to all Christianity, to join the Brotherhood and to support a Turkish campaign planned by the emperor for the following year, but without finding much interest. He gave the knights who would take part in this campaign the privilege of wearing a crown in their coat of arms and thus created the status of the \"crowned knight\".<ref>Manfred Hollegger \"Maximilian I.\" (2005), p 150.</ref>\n\nEmpress [[Maria Theresa]] is said to have issued new statutes of the order in 1765.\n\n[[Franz Joseph I of Austria|Emperor Franz Joseph I]] confirmed the priory of the Order of St. George in Austria in 1848.\n\nIn 1917 [[Charles I of Austria|Emperor Charles I]] confirmed the order as a purely secular order of knights in the future.<ref>Roman Proch\u00e1zka \"\u00d6sterreichisches Ordenshandbuch\" (1979), p 274.</ref>  \n\nBetween 1919 and 1920 the order structures were modernized by persons approved by the emperor. Due to the situation in exile of the imperial family, the leadership of the order then went to [[Prince Johannes of Liechtenstein (1873\u20131959)|Prince Johannes of Liechtenstein]], although the title of protector and holder of the order remained with the House of Habsburg.\n\nThen there was a need to adapt the statutes of the order to modern conditions. On February 7, 1926, a constitutional reorganization council in Hanover issued a new order, whereby the nobility was no longer required for admission and the order was given the name \"Old St. George Knightly Order, also known as the Order of the Four Roman Emperors\". The order continued to claim that the unity and interests of the Central European peoples and nations were guaranteed for centuries by the Holy Roman Empire and the Habsburg monarchy.[[File:Oliver Mark - Otto Habsburg-Lothringen, P\u00f6cking 2006.jpg|thumb|Archduke [[Otto von Habsburg]]]]\n\nIn 1935, due to the political situation in the German Reich, the seat of the order was moved to Salzburg, from where he stood up against National Socialism, for [[Central Europe]] independent of Nazi Germany and for the re-establishment of the House of Habsburg. In 1938, after the annexation of Austria, the order was banned and dissolved by the Nazis for political reasons.<ref>Johannes Krejci \"Aus der Geschichte des Alten Ordens vom St. Georg.\", Wien 2002.</ref> Many who campaigned for Habsburg during the Nazi era were killed, taken to a concentration camp, or persecuted by the Gestapo.<ref>Elisabeth Boeckl-Klamper, Thomas Mang, Wolfgang Neugebauer \"Gestapo-Leitstelle Wien 1938\u20131945.\" Vienna 2018, p 299\u2013305.</ref><ref>Hans Schafranek \"Widerstand und Verrat: Gestapospitzel im antifaschistischen Untergrund.\" Vienna 2017, p 161\u2013248.</ref> The House of Habsburg was an early supporter of European integration and a vehement opponent of [[National Socialism]] and [[Communism]].<ref>Timothy Snyder \"The Red Prince: The Secret Lives of a Habsburg Archduke\" (2008); James Longo \"Hitler and the Habsburgs: The Fuhrer's Vendetta Against the Austrian Royals\" (2018).</ref>\n\nDuring communism, former members of the order or other Habsburg supporters were persecuted behind the [[Iron Curtain]] because the communist regimes feared opposition in their oppressed countries.\n\nThe cancellation of the \"Old Order of St. George\" (also called \"Order of the Four Roman Emperors\") by Nazi Germany in 1935/1938 was reversed by the reorganization convention on January 18, 2008. Because after the fall of the Iron Curtain and due to the complete independence of the new Central European countries from the USSR, there was now the possibility and need to reactivate communities in order to connect the peoples in this area. Archduke [[Otto von Habsburg]], Archduke [[Karl von Habsburg]] and  [[Vincenz Liechtenstein|Prince Vincenz of Liechtenstein]] were significantly involved.\n\nAt the convent on April 30, 2011, Archduke Karl von Habsburg confirmed the \u201cSt. Order of George - A European order of the House of Habsburg-Lorraine\" as an order of the [[House of Habsburg]]. Building on the centuries-old Habsburg motto \" [[Viribus Unitis]]\", the peoples and nations of Central Europe should now take care of their interests together. In the framework of this European Habsburg Order, the historical connections are to be strengthened and expanded, also in order to be able to perform better in United Europe. The Order sees it as its task to recognize and preserve the common cultural, scientific and interpersonal heritage of Central Europe.<ref>Regarding the Habsburg tradition in this regard: Moritz Csaky \"Pluralit\u00e9 culturelle et identit\u00e9: Criteres d\u00b4 une auto-reconnaissance transnationale sous la Monarchie des Habsbourg\" Les Temps Modernes 48:550 (1992), p 154.</ref> The model is the tolerant Habsburg approach to the national diversity of the peoples of Central Europe.<ref>Paul Miller-Melamed and Claire Morelon \"What the Hapsburg Empire Got Right\" in New York Times, 10 September 2019.</ref><ref>Johannes Feichtinger, Gary B. Cohen \"Understanding multiculturalism: The Habsburg central European experience\" (2014).</ref><ref>William M. Johnston, \"The Political and Cultural Background of Vienna 1900: A Golden Age of Cultural Exchange\" (Melbourne 2011).</ref>\n\nThe members of the order should also use those Habsburg roots that extend beyond Central Europe, for example to Italy, Switzerland, Spain, France, Great Britain, Germany, the Benelux countries and the Orient. Accordingly, the \u201cSt. Order of George - A European order of the House of Habsburg-Lorraine\" has a close relationship with the \"Austrian pilgrim hospice for the Holy Family\" in Jerusalem, which was donated by Emperor Franz Joseph I for all people of the Habsburg monarchy.<ref>[https://www.austrianhospice.com/ Austrian Pilgrim Hospice to the Holy Family in Jerusalem]</ref>\n\nRegarding the necessary moral attitude of a St. Georg knight today, Bishop Klaus K\u00fcng said during an investiture in Budapest: \"When it comes to values \u200b\u200bthat are of great importance to human development, it is necessary to stand up for them courageously. What are these values? - Ultimately, it's Christian values.\" But that also means that the order in Habsburg tradition is particularly dedicated to the peaceful balance between religions and the intercultural encounter between [[Christianity]], [[Judaism]]<ref>The House of Habsburg already vehemently opposed anti-Semitism in the 19th century. For example, Emperor Franz Joseph I said: Anti-Semitism should be exterminated. See in detail: Robert S. Wistrich \"Die Juden Wiens im Zeitalter Kaiser Franz Josephs - The Jews of Vienna in the Age of Franz Joseph\" (Oxford 1994), p 149.</ref> and [[Islam]]<ref>As early as 1912 (- through the annexation of Bosnia and Herzegovina under state law in 1908, 600,000 Muslims belonged to the k.u.k. Monarchy) was the guarantee of free and public religious practice of the Muslims regulated in the Habsburg monarchy. Bosnian Muslims got the highest Awards for bravery and loyalty and provided the bodyguard of the emperor. [http://www.bundesheer.at/pdf_pool/publikationen/ms_23_5.pdf European military pastoral care between Christianity, Islam and secularization - Austrian Armed Forces]</ref>.<ref>On Habsburg and the diversity of religions: Pieter M. Judson \"The Habsburg Empire. A New History\" (Harvard 2016).</ref>\n\nIn addition to local meetings, the order has major events such as in Vienna, Budapest, Prague, Zagreb, Ljubljana, Trieste, Milan, London, Frankfurt, Salzburg and Tyrol.\n\nThe admission was and is a special privilege and a great honor.\n[[File:Insignie des St. Georgs-Orden (Habsburg-Lothringen).png|thumb|Insignia of the Order of St. George]]\n\n== Notable members ==\n{{div col|colwidth=18em}}\n*{{flagicon|AUT}} [[Duchess Eilika of Oldenburg|Archduchess Eilika]]<ref name=\"ordensregierung\"/>\n*{{flagicon|NLD}} [[Jan Peter Balkenende]]\n*{{flagicon|SVK}} [[J\u00e1n \u010carnogursk\u00fd]]\n*{{flagicon|ITA}} [[Luis Durnwalder]]\n*{{flagicon|ITA}} [[Massimiliano Fedriga]]\n*{{flagicon|AUT}} [[Norbert Hofer]]\n*{{flagicon|MKD}} [[Gjorge Ivanov]]\n*{{flagicon|AUT}} [[Karlheinz Kopf]]\n*{{flagicon|GBR}} [[David Mackintosh (politician)|David Mackintosh]]\n*{{flagicon|ITA}} [[Roberto Maroni]]\n*{{flagicon|AUT}} [[Siegfried Nagl]]\n*{{flagicon|AUT}} [[Harald Ofner]]\n*{{flagicon|BUL}} [[Rosen Plevneliev]]\n*{{flagicon|AUT}} [[Erwin Pr\u00f6ll]]\n*{{flagicon|AUT}} [[Josef P\u00fchringer]]\n*{{flagicon|GBR}} [[George Robertson, Baron Robertson of Port Ellen|Baron Robertson of Port Ellen]]\n*{{flagicon|ITA}} [[Luigi Roth]]\n*{{flagicon|AUT}} [[Franz Schausberger]]\n*{{flagicon|GER}} [[Peter Schmitz]]\n*{{flagicon|HUN}} [[Zsolt Semj\u00e9n]]\n*{{flagicon|AUT}} [[Herwig van Staa]]\n*{{flagicon|GBR}} [[David Steel|Lord Steel of Aikwood]]\n*{{flagicon|AUT}} [[Ursula Stenzel]]\n*{{flagicon|SLO}} [[Verica Trstenjak]]\n*{{flagicon|GBR}} [[Alan Watson, Baron Watson of Richmond|Baron Watson of Richmond]]\n{{div col end}}\n<small>Source: [https://www.georgsorden.at/struktur/die-ordensregierung/ Ehrenritter]</small>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://www.karlvonhabsburg.at/organisationen/sankt-georgs-orden/ History of the former National Order and the current Chartered Dynastic Order]\n*[https://www.georgsorden.at/ Official website]\n*[https://www.facebook.com/georgsorden Facebook Page]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Order of St. George}}\n[[Category:Orders of chivalry of Austria]]\n[[Category:House of Habsburg]]\n\n{{Austria-org-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: an European \u2192 a European", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Order_of_St._George_(Habsburg-Lorraine)"}
{"title_page": "Francesco Totti", "text_new": "{{redirect|Totti|the Italian boxer|Benito Totti|the Cape Verdean footballer who's also known as Totti|Wuilito Fernandes}}\n{{short description|Italian association football player}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Francesco Totti\n| image = KL-2018 (4).jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = Totti in 2018\n| fullname = Francesco Totti<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/players/tottidata.html|title=Francesco Totti - Goals in Serie A|website=RSSSF|first=Roberto|last=Di Maggio|accessdate=18 February 2017}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1976|9|27}}<ref name=\"ASROMA-Profile\">{{cite web|url=http://www.asroma.com/en/teams/players-and-staff/francesco-totti|title=Francesco Totti|publisher=A.S. Roma|language=Italian|accessdate=29 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180703163415/http://www.asroma.com/en/teams/players-and-staff/francesco-totti|archive-date=3 July 2018|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Rome]], Italy\n| height = 1.80 m<ref name=legaseriea>{{cite web|url=http://www.legaseriea.it/it/giocatori/francesco-totti/TOTFR|title=Francesco Totti|publisher=Lega Serie A|language=it|accessdate=6 September 2015}}</ref>\n| currentclub = \n| clubnumber = \n| position = [[Midfielder#Attacking midfielder|Attacking midfielder]] / [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n| youthyears1 = 1983\u20131984\n| youthclubs1 = Fortitudo Luditor\n| youthyears2 = 1984\u20131986\n| youthclubs2 = [[A.S.D. Trastevere Calcio|Smit Trastevere]]\n| youthyears3 = 1986\u20131989\n| youthclubs3 = [[A.S. Lodigiani|Lodigiani]]\n| youthyears4 = 1989\u20131992\n| youthclubs4 = [[A.S. Roma|Roma]]\n| years1 = 1992\u20132017\n| clubs1 = [[A.S. Roma|Roma]]\n| caps1 = 618<!-- LEAGUE APPEARANCES ONLY -->\n| goals1 = 250<!-- LEAGUE GOALS ONLY -->\n| nationalyears1 = 1992\n| nationalteam1 = [[Italy national under-16 football team|Italy U15]]<!--At that time U15 was equal to U16-->\n| nationalcaps1 = 6\n| nationalgoals1 = 3\n| nationalyears2 = 1991\u20131992\n| nationalteam2 = [[Italy national under-17 football team|Italy U16]]<!--At that time U16 was equal to U17-->\n| nationalcaps2 = 13\n| nationalgoals2 = 2\n| nationalyears3 = 1993\u20131995\n| nationalteam3 = [[Italy national under-19 football team|Italy U18]] <!--At that time U18 was equal to U19-->\n| nationalcaps3 = 14\n| nationalgoals3 = 7\n| nationalyears4 = 1995\u20131997\n| nationalteam4 = [[Italy national under-21 football team|Italy U21]]\n| nationalcaps4 = 8\n| nationalgoals4 = 4\n| nationalyears5 = 1997\n| nationalteam5 = [[Italy at the Olympics|Italy U23]]\n| nationalcaps5 = 4\n| nationalgoals5 = 2\n| nationalyears6 = 1998\u20132006\n| nationalteam6 = [[Italy national football team|Italy]]\n| nationalcaps6 = 58\n| nationalgoals6 = 9\n| medaltemplates = {{Medal|Sport|Men's [[Association football|football]]}}\n{{Medal|Country|{{fb|ITA}}}}\n{{Medal|Comp|[[FIFA World Cup]]}}\n{{Medal|W|[[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006 Germany]]|}}\n{{Medal|Comp|[[UEFA European Championship]]}}\n{{Medal|RU|[[UEFA Euro 2000|2000 Belgium-Netherlands]]|}}\n{{Medal|Comp|[[UEFA European Under-21 Championship]]|}}\n{{Medal|W|[[1996 UEFA European Under-21 Football Championship|1996 Spain]]|}}\n{{Medal|Comp|[[UEFA European Under-19 Championship|UEFA European Under-18 Championship]]|}}\n{{Medal|RU|[[1995 UEFA European Under-18 Championship|1995 Greece]]|}}\n{{Medal|Comp|[[UEFA European Under-17 Championship|UEFA European Under-16 Championship]]|}}\n{{Medal|RU|[[1993 UEFA European Under-16 Championship|1993 Turkey]]|}}\n{{Medal|Comp|[[Mediterranean Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1997 Mediterranean Games|1997 Bari]]|}}\n}}\n\n'''Francesco Totti''' {{postnominals|post-noms=[[Order of Merit of the Italian Republic|Ufficiale OMRI]]}}<ref name=\"Presidenza della Repubblica\">{{cite web|url=http://www.quirinale.it/elementi/DettaglioOnorificenze.aspx?decorato=198829|title=Ufficiale Ordine al Merito della Repubblica Italiana|date=12 December 2006|publisher=Presidenza della Repubblica|language=Italian|accessdate=6 September 2015}}</ref> ({{IPA-it|fran\u02c8t\u0283esko \u02c8t\u0254tti}};<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dipionline.it/dizionario/ricerca?lemma=Francesco|title=Francesco|work=DiPI Online|author=[[Luciano Canepari]]|accessdate=26 October 2018|language=it}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dipionline.it/dizionario/ricerca?lemma=Totti|title=Totti|work=DiPI Online|author=Luciano Canepari|accessdate=26 October 2018|language=it}}</ref> born 27 September 1976) is an Italian former professional [[Association football|footballer]] who played for [[A.S. Roma|Roma]] and the [[Italy national football team|Italy national team]] primarily as an [[Midfielder#Attacking midfielder|attacking midfielder]] or [[Forward (association football)#Second striker|second striker]], but could also play as a lone [[Forward (association football)#Striker|striker]] or [[Forward (association football)#Winger|winger]]. He is often referred to as ''Er Bimbo de Oro'' (The Golden Boy), ''L'Ottavo Re di Roma'' (The Eighth King of Rome), ''Er Pupone'' (The Big Baby), ''Il Capitano''  (The Captain), and ''Il Gladiatore'' (The Gladiator) by the Italian sports media. A creative offensive [[playmaker]] renowned for his vision, technique, and goalscoring ability, Totti is considered to be one of the greatest Italian players of all time, one of the best players of his generation, and Roma's greatest ever player.\n\nTotti [[List of one-club men in association football|spent his entire career]] at Roma, winning a [[Serie A]] title, two [[Coppa Italia]] titles, and two [[Supercoppa Italiana]] titles. He is the [[Football records in Italy#Goalscoring|second-highest scorer of all time]] in Italian league history with 250 goals, and is the [[Football records in Italy#Highest-scoring Italian players in all competitions|sixth-highest scoring Italian in all competitions]] with 316 goals.<ref name=\"Goals\">{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzettagiallorossa.it/2013/03/as-roma-totti-a-caccia-del-record/|title=AS ROMA Totti a caccia del record|work=Gazzetta Giallorossa|accessdate=18 February 2015|language=Italian}}</ref> Totti is the [[A.S. Roma statistics and records#Top all-time goalscorers|top goalscorer]] and the [[A.S. Roma statistics and records#All competitions appearances|most capped player]] in Roma's history, holds the record for the most goals scored in Serie A while playing for a single club, and also holds the record for the youngest club captain in the history of Serie A. In November 2014, Totti extended his record as the oldest goalscorer in [[UEFA Champions League]] history, aged 38 years and 59 days.\n\nA [[2006 FIFA World Cup]] winner and [[UEFA Euro 2000]] finalist with [[Italy national football team|Italy]], Totti was selected in the All-Star team for both tournaments; he also represented his country at the [[2002 FIFA World Cup|2002 World Cup]] and [[UEFA Euro 2004|Euro 2004]]. In 2007, Totti announced his international retirement due to recurring physical problems<ref name=\":0\" /> and in order to focus solely on club play with Roma.<ref name=\"gazzetta.it\" />\n\nTotti won a record eleven [[Oscar del Calcio]] awards from the [[Italian Footballers' Association]]: five [[Serie A Italian Footballer of the Year]] awards, two [[Serie A Footballer of the Year]] awards, two Serie A Goal of the Year awards, one Serie A Goalscorer of the Year award, and one [[Serie A Young Footballer of the Year]] award. He also won the 2007 [[European Golden Shoe]] and the 2010 [[Golden Foot]]. Totti was selected in the [[European Sports Media|European Sports Media team of the season]] three times.  In 2004, he was named in the [[FIFA 100]], a list of the world's greatest living players as selected by [[Pel\u00e9]], as part of [[FIFA]]'s centenary celebrations.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/3533891.stm|title=Pele's list of the greatest|date=4 March 2004|accessdate=31 May 2011|work=BBC Sport}}</ref> In 2011, Totti was recognised by [[International Federation of Football History & Statistics|IFFHS]] as the most popular footballer in Europe.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.iffhs.de/?32a00e42f0ae2300bf11504e52d17f7370eff3702bb1c2bbb6e28e05|title=The World's Most Popular Footballer Amongst Currently Active Players in 2011|accessdate=25 January 2012|publisher=IFFHS.de|language=}}</ref> In 2015, ''[[France Football]]'' rated him as one of the ten-best footballers in the world who are over age 36.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.francefootball.fr/news/Le-top-10-des-meilleurs-vieux/559763|title=Le top 10 des meilleurs vieux|trans-title=The top 10 of the best oldies|publisher=France Football|language=French|author1=Thomas Simon|date=19 May 2015|accessdate=5 February 2019}}</ref> Following his retirement in 2017, Totti was awarded the [[Globe Soccer Awards|Player's Career Award]] and the [[UEFA President's Award]].\n\n==Early life==\nTotti was born in [[Rome]] to parents Lorenzo and Fiorella Totti. He was raised in the [[Porta Metronia]] neighbourhood.<ref name=\"Totti&nbsp;\u2014 Archivio Storico Gazzetta\">{{cite news|first=Gaetano|last=Imparato|title=Francesco Totti|url=http://archiviostorico.gazzetta.it/1998/aprile/25/FARNCESCO_TOTTI_gm_0_980425207.shtml|work=La Gazzetta dello Sport|accessdate=4 June 2015|language=Italian|format=25 April 1998}}</ref> As a youngster he idolised ex-Roma captain [[Giuseppe Giannini]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://archiviostorico.gazzetta.it/1997/luglio/19/Roma_scelto_nuovo_Principe_Totti_ga_0_9707193484.shtml|title=La Roma ha scelto un nuovo Principe: Totti|work=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|first=Gaetano|last=Imparato|date=19 July 1997|accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref> and regularly played football with older boys.<ref name=\"Rome's greatest son\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/long-read-francesco-totti-romes-greatest-son-who-never-got-love-he-deserved#:isr8gB319QtYcA|title=The long read: Francesco Totti \u2013 Rome's greatest son who never got the love he deserved|last=Murray|first=Andrew|date=1 April 2016|magazine=FourFourTwo|accessdate=12 April 2016}}</ref> Totti began to play youth team football at the age of 8, with Fortitudo, later joining SMIT Trastevere and [[A.S. Lodigiani|Lodigiani]]. After he came to the attention of scouts, his mother refused a lucrative offer from [[A.C. Milan|Milan]] in order to keep him in his home town. Although his youth club initially had come to an agreement to sell Totti to the [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio youth side]], one of [[A.S. Roma|Roma's youth coaches]], Gildo Giannini, persuaded his parents to let him join the [[A.S. Roma Primavera|Roma youth squad]] in 1989.<ref name=\"Totti&nbsp;\u2014 Archivio Storico Gazzetta\"/>\n\n==Club career==\n===Roma===\n====1992\u20131997 Early seasons====\nAfter three years in the youth team, Totti made his first appearance for [[A.S. Roma|Roma]]'s senior side in [[Serie A]] at the age of 16, when coach [[Vujadin Bo\u0161kov]] called him up in the 2\u20130 away victory against [[Brescia Calcio|Brescia]] on 28 March [[1992\u201393 Serie A|1993]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.corrieredellosport.it/calcio/serie_a/roma/2015/03/28-402429/Totti,+22+anni+fa+l%27esordio+in+Serie+A+con+la+Roma|title=Totti, 22 anni fa l'esordio in Serie A con la Roma|work=Corriere dello Sport|language=Italian|date=28 March 2015|accessdate=26 July 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160807121900/http://www.corrieredellosport.it/calcio/serie_a/roma/2015/03/28-402429/Totti,+22+anni+fa+l%27esordio+in+Serie+A+con+la+Roma|archivedate=7 August 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In the following season under [[Carlo Mazzone]], Totti began to play more regularly as a second striker,<ref name=\"Never imagined being striker\">{{cite web|url=http://www.football-italia.net/76826/totti-%E2%80%98never-imagined-being-striker%E2%80%99|title=Totti: \u2018Never imagined being striker\u2019|publisher=Football Italia|date=8 December 2015|accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref> and scored his first goal on 4 September [[1994\u201395 Serie A|1994]] in a 1\u20131 draw against [[Foggia Calcio|Foggia]].<ref name=\"Rome's greatest son\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/1994/settembre/05/ragazzino_illude_poi_Roma_litiga_co_0_94090511607.shtml|title=il ragazzino illude, poi la Roma litiga|date=5 September 1994|work=Corriere della Sera|accessdate=26 July 2016|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120712232407/http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/1994/settembre/05/ragazzino_illude_poi_Roma_litiga_co_0_94090511607.shtml|archivedate=12 July 2012|url-status=dead|page=39|language=Italian|df=dmy}}</ref> By 1995, Totti had become a regular in Roma's starting line-up and scored 16 goals during the next three seasons, while creating several more, as his talent was praised by his manager Mazzone.<ref name=\"Never imagined being striker\"/><ref name=\"mazzone-totti\">{{cite news|url=http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/1995/gennaio/10/Totti_gioiello_cassaforte_co_10_9501102871.shtml|title=Totti, gioiello in cassaforte|work=Corriere della Sera|first=Luigi|last=Coldagelli|page=38|date=10 January 1995|accessdate=25 July 2016|language=Italian}}</ref>\n\nFollowing Mazzone's sacking in the summer of 1996 and the departure of Giannini, Totti was expected to play a more prominent role, after several promising seasons; however, the team underperformed during the [[1996\u201397 Serie A|1996\u201397 season]], while Totti struggled to gain playing time under new manager [[Carlos Bianchi]], and was even set to leave for [[U.C. Sampdoria|Sampdoria]] on loan in January 1997. Roma's chairman at the time however, [[Franco Sensi]], impeded the transfer, leading to further tensions with the manager, who eventually parted ways with the club.<ref name=\"Rome's greatest son\"/><ref name=\"La leggenda continua\">{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Squadre/Roma/27-09-2013/roma-buon-compleanno-totti-leggenda-continua-201244195813.shtml|title=Roma, buon compleanno Totti. La leggenda continua|work=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|first=Marco|last=Calabresi|date=27 September 2013|accessdate=15 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n====1997\u20131999: Emergence as Roma's number 10 and captain on the left wing====\nTotti's years under [[Zden\u011bk Zeman]] represented a period of both physical and mental maturation as a player. From a technical and tactical standpoint, he proved to be compatible on the left wing in the rigid formations of the Bohemian coach, as his new role gave him more space to take on defenders in one on one situations, and cut into the centre to shoot on goal with his stronger foot;<ref name=\"Rome's greatest son\"/><ref name=\"Never imagined being striker\"/> he also became physically more powerful, fit, hard-working, and complete.<ref name=\"Totti, pi\u00f9 muscoli al servizio della fantasia\"/> He displayed a greater responsibility for the team, and was presented with the [[Squad number (association football)|number 10]] jersey.<ref name=\"Rome's greatest son\"/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Imparato|first1=Gaetano|title=La Roma ha scelto un nuovo Principe: Totti|url=http://archiviostorico.gazzetta.it/1997/luglio/19/Roma_scelto_nuovo_Principe_Totti_ga_0_9707193484.shtml|work=La Gazzetta dello Sport|accessdate=26 July 2016|language=Italian|date=19 July 1997}}</ref> His first season under Zeman started well, with Totti taking advantage of a [[Formation (association football)#4.E2.80.933.E2.80.933|4\u20133\u20133 formation]] and making his breakthrough with the club.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tg1.rai.it/dl/tg1/2010/articoli/ContentItem-308fc4fa-288f-45b9-8e9b-349cbb86357c.html|title=Roma, Zeman \u00e8 tornato|publisher=Rai.it|language=Italian|date=4 June 2012|accessdate=15 August 2016}}</ref> He finished the league season reaching double figures in goals scored for the first time in his career;<ref name=\"La leggenda continua\"/> including a goal in the club's 2\u20130 away win against [[S.S.C. Napoli|Napoli]] on 22 February 1998,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/it/news/2/serie-a/2010/09/30/2144284/langolo-de-laroma24it-altro-che-cornetto-il-portafortuna|title=L'angolo de \"Laroma24.it\" - Altro che cornetto, il portafortuna della Roma \u00e8... il San Paolo|publisher=Goal.com|language=Italian|first=Filippo|last=Limoncelli|date=30 September 2010|accessdate=15 August 2016}}</ref> Totti scored 13 goals in Serie A in total,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.raisport.rai.it/mcalcio/978a/c00045.htm|title=Serie A 1997/98: Francesco TOTTI|publisher=Rai.it|language=Italian|accessdate=15 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180710195123/http://www2.raisport.rai.it/mcalcio/978a/c00045.htm|archive-date=10 July 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> and contributed to Roma's fourth place league finish that year.<ref name=\"Italy Championship 1997/98\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesi/ital98.html|title=Italy Championship 1997/98|website=RSSSF|first=Maurizio|last=Mariani|date=29 November 2000|accessdate=15 August 2016}}</ref> Although he was not called up for the [[1998 FIFA World Cup]] by Italy manager [[Cesare Maldini]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/1998/maggio/23/Totti_Fedele_alla_Roma_co_10_9805231931.shtml |title=Totti: Fedele alla Roma |work= Corriere della Sera |language=Italian |first=Franco |last=Melli |date=23 May 1998 |accessdate=15 August 2016 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151031025823/http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/1998/maggio/23/Totti_Fedele_alla_Roma_co_10_9805231931.shtml |archivedate=31 October 2015 |df=dmy }}</ref> his consistent performances, creativity and goalscoring throughout the course of the previous Serie A season saw him being awarded the [[Guerin d'Oro]] for the [[1997\u201398 Serie A|1997\u201398 season]], given to him for having achieved the highest average rating of any Serie A player.<ref name=\"Guerin d'Oro\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/italpoy.html |title=Italy&nbsp;\u2013 Footballer of the Year |website=RSSSF |accessdate=6 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150121013030/http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/italpoy.html |archivedate=21 January 2015 |df=dmy }}</ref> The following season, he began to gain recognition as a club symbol and as a leader,<ref name=\"Rome's greatest son\"/> and on 31 October 1998, Totti became the official team captain, and the youngest Serie A club captain ever at the age of 22, inheriting the armband from [[Aldair]].<ref name=\"Totti: Serie A's youngest captain\">{{cite news|url=https://www.facebook.com/serieatim/photos/a.471212169618120.1073741847.124858950920112/1009953815743950/?type=3|title=Totti diventa il pi\u00f9 giovane capitano nella storia della Serie A TIM. |accessdate=19 October 2015|work=Serie A Facebook Page|date=16 October 2015}}</ref> On 29 November 1998, Totti scored the equalising goal in a 3\u20133 draw against cross-city rivals [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]]; this was his first ever goal in the [[Derby della Capitale|Rome Derby]].<ref name=\"Rome's greatest son\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.repubblica.it/sport/calcio/serie-a/roma/2016/03/31/news/totti_verso_derby-136625114/|title=Roma, Totti e il derby: una magia di gol ed esultanze. Ma il pi\u00f9 'triste' potrebbe essere l'ultimo|work=la Repubblica|language=Italian|first=Matteo|last=Monti|date=31 March 2016|accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref> Overall, he scored 30 goals and provided 26 assists during Zeman's two-year managerial stint.<ref name=\"Rome's greatest son\"/> For his performances, he was named the [[Serie A Young Footballer of the Year]] for the [[1998\u201399 Serie A|1998\u201399]] season.<ref name=\"ASROMA-Profile\" />\n\n====1999\u20132004: The ''Scudetto'' as a playmaker====\n[[File:Totti-a.s.Roma-celebration.jpg|thumb|Decal of Totti alongside the ''Scudetto'' shield, displayed on a house in Rome]]\n\nIn June 1999, Roma's then-president Franco Sensi sacked Zeman and signed [[Fabio Capello]] as a replacement, with the aim of winning the league title.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.raisport.rai.it/news/sport/calcio/199906/02/37555e8904721/|title=Addio Zeman|publisher=Rai Sport|language=Italian|date=2 June 1999|accessdate=27 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180712125030/http://www2.raisport.rai.it/news/sport/calcio/199906/02/37555e8904721/|archive-date=12 July 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> By the [[2000\u201301 Serie A|2000\u201301]] campaign under the new coach, Roma were building a competitive team around Totti, who was by now being utilised as a creative [[Midfielder#Attacking midfielder|attacking midfielder]] by Capello in a [[Formation (association football)#3.E2.80.934.E2.80.931.E2.80.932|3\u20134\u20131\u20132 formation]], due to his passing skills and [[Playmaker|playmaking]] abilities.<ref name=Versatility>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/versatility-helps-totti-remain-romas-man-all-seasons|title=Versatility helps Totti remain Roma's man for all seasons|magazine=FourFourTwo|first=Michael|last=Cox|date=4 October 2013|accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzettaworld.com/news/serie-a/roma/totti-trequartista-role-frosinone/|title=Roma captain Totti to be given new role against Frosinone|work=La Gazzetta dello Sport|first=Marco|last=Credentino|date=10 September 2015|accessdate=29 July 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160819170911/http://www.gazzettaworld.com/news/serie-a/roma/totti-trequartista-role-frosinone/|archivedate=19 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2007/dec/14/newsstory.sport17|title=How Capello won his nine league titles|work=The Guardian|first1=Paolo|last1=Bandini|first2=Sid|last2=Lowe|date=14 December 2007|accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref> Totti scored in a 2\u20130 home win over [[Bologna F.C. 1909|Bologna]] on his season debut on 1 October 2000.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.repubblica.it/online/campionato/roma/roma/roma.html|title=Totti-gol regala un sorriso alla Roma|work=la Repubblica|language=Italian|date=1 October 2000|accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref> On 10 December, Totti scored the match-winning goal in a 2\u20131 home win against [[Udinese Calcio|Udinese]] with a powerful left-footed volley to help Roma to their fifth home win of the season.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.repubblica.it/online/campionato_partite/romaudinese/romaudinese/romaudinese.html|title=Una magia di Totti trascina la Roma|work=la Repubblica|language=Italian|date=10 December 2000|accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref> He continued his goalscoring form by scoring against Napoli at home in a 3\u20130 victory on 28 January 2001, as Roma finished the first half of the league season in first place.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.repubblica.it/online/campionato_partite/romanapoli/romanapoli/romanapoli.html|title=La Roma ad un passo dal titolo d'inverno|work=la Repubblica|language=Italian|date=28 January 2001|accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.raisport.rai.it/news/sport/calcio/200101/28/3a74626e054c3/|title=Roma campione d'inverno|publisher=RaiSport|language=Italian|date=28 January 2001|accessdate=29 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180712121122/http://www2.raisport.rai.it/news/sport/calcio/200101/28/3a74626e054c3/|archive-date=12 July 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> Totti continued to play an important role in keeping the club at the top of the table throughout the remainder of the season, gaining a comfortable lead over rivals [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/1299925.stm|title=Rome giants in title crunch|work=BBC Sport|date=27 April 2001|accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref> On 17 June 2001, at the [[Stadio Olimpico]], Roma beat [[S.S.D. Parma Calcio 1913|Parma]] 3\u20131, with their three main attackers, Totti, [[Vincenzo Montella]] and [[Gabriel Batistuta]] scoring one goal each, as Roma were crowned champions of Italy for the third time in their history.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.repubblica.it/online/campionato_partite/romaparma/romaparma/romaparma.html|title=Roma, show all'Olimpico per la festa scudetto|work=la Repubblica|language=Italian|date=17 June 2011|accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref> Totti finished the league season with 13 goals, equalling what was at the time his personal goalscoring record in a single Serie A season.<ref name=\"Rome's greatest son\"/>\n\nOn 19 August 2001 Totti won his first [[2001 Supercoppa Italiana|Supercoppa Italiana]], scoring and assisting in the 3\u20130 win against [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.raisport.rai.it/news/rubriche/coppe978/200108/19/3b800d4b05ba6/|title=SupeRoma Supercoppa|publisher=RaiSport|language=Italian|date=19 August 2001|accessdate=29 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181223121320/http://www2.raisport.rai.it/news/rubriche/coppe978/200108/19/3b800d4b05ba6/|archive-date=23 December 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> Totti was named the [[Serie A Italian Footballer of the Year]] for both 2000 and 2001,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.repubblica.it/online/calcio/oscarpar/oscarpar/oscarpar.html|title=Oscar: Zidane batte Totti \u00e8 lui il pi\u00f9 bravo calciatore|work=la Repubblica|language=Italian|date=2 October 2001|accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Oscar-del-Calcio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.assocalciatori.it/Pagine/AlbodOro/tabid/161/language/en-US/Default.aspx |title=Albo d'Oro |publisher=AIC |language=Italian |accessdate=29 July 2016 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111223192332/http://www.assocalciatori.it/Pagine/AlbodOro/tabid/161/language/en-US/Default.aspx |archivedate=23 December 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref> and won the [[Serie A Footballer of the Year]] Award for the first time in his career in 2000.<ref name=\"Guerin d'Oro\"/> He received his first [[Ballon d'Or]] nomination in [[2000 Ballon d'Or|2000]], finishing 14th in voting, and fifth the [[2001 Ballon d'Or|following year]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www2.raisport.rai.it/news/sport/calcio/200112/17/3c1e290503e87/|title=A Owen il Pallone d'Oro|publisher=RaiSport|language=Italian|date=17 December 2001|accessdate=31 May 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120513201702/http://www2.raisport.rai.it/news/sport/calcio/200112/17/3c1e290503e87/|archive-date=13 May 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> Due to his performances and leadership, Totti had established himself as a hero to the Roma fans, who were also able to identify with his background as a Roma native and lifelong supporter.<ref name=\"Rome's greatest son\"/>\n\nOver the following seasons, Totti played in a free role as either a forward or second striker in a [[Formation (association football)#3\u20135\u20132|3\u20135\u20132 formation]], often alongside either Batistuta or the newly acquired youngster [[Antonio Cassano]].<ref name=\"Never imagined being striker\"/> He scored his first hat-trick in Serie A, in a 3\u20132 away win over [[Brescia Calcio|Brescia]] on 30 September 2002.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://archiviostorico.gazzetta.it/2002/settembre/30/pensa_Totti_ga_0_0209304391.shtml|title=Ci pensa Totti|work=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|first1=Massimo|last1=Cecchini|first2=Luigi|last2=Garlando |date=30 September 2002|accessdate=16 February 2016}}</ref> Totti also scored the only goal in Roma's decisive 1\u20130 victory at the [[Santiago Bernab\u00e9u Stadium]] against [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]] on 30 October 2002; this was the first time in 35 years that an Italian team had won a match in [[Madrid]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.corrieredellosport.it/624/2011/10/30-201566/2002+Champions+League,+Totti+eroe+a+Madrid|title=2002 Champions League, Totti eroe a Madrid|work=Corriere dello Sport|language=Italian|date=30 October 2011|accessdate=13 April 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140414165659/http://www.corrieredellosport.it/624/2011/10/30-201566/2002+Champions+League,+Totti+eroe+a+Madrid|archivedate=14 April 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He continued his goalscoring exploits against [[Valencia CF|Valencia]], scoring two goals in Roma's 3\u20130 win.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/champions_league/2797715.stm|title=Totti shoots down Valencia|work=BBC Sport|date=25 February 2003|accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref> Despite this, Roma only finished third in their [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] group, and in eighth position in Serie A,<ref name=\"Italy 2002/03\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesi/ital03.html|title=Italy 2002/03|website=RSSSF|first1=Dario|last1=Desio|first2=Giacomo|last2=Giusti|first3=Francesco|last3=Gullo|date=31 August 2003|accessdate=20 October 2015}}</ref> although they managed to reach the [[2003 Coppa Italia Final|2003 Coppa Italia final]]. In the final against Milan, Totti scored three times from free kicks over both legs (one goal at home and two at the [[San Siro]]), but Roma lost out to Milan 6\u20133 on aggregate.<ref name=\"Al Milan anche la Coppa Italia\">{{cite news|url=http://www.repubblica.it/online/calcio2002_serie_a/milancop/milancop/milancop.html|title=Al Milan anche la Coppa Italia|work=la Repubblica|accessdate=25 July 2014}}</ref> In 2003, Totti won his second Serie A Footballer of the Year Award.<ref name=\"Guerin d'Oro\"/>\n\nIn the [[2003\u201304 Serie A|2003\u201304 season]], Totti played a key role as Roma finished runner-up to Milan in the ''[[Scudetto]]'' race.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesi/ital04.html |title=Italy 2003/04 |website=RSSSF |first1=Andrea |last1=Ferrigno |first2=Giacomo |last2=Giusti |date=19 August 2005 |accessdate=22 October 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160207154304/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesi/ital04.html |archivedate=7 February 2016 |df=dmy }}</ref> Throughout the league season, he scored 20 goals, his best haul in Serie A up to that point, which allowed him to win his second Guerin d'Oro as the player with the best average rating in Serie A throughout the season.<ref name=\"Guerin d'Oro\"/> Moreover, the Roma captain notably scored trademark chipped goals on two occasions throughout the season, against Brescia and [[Empoli F.C.|Empoli]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.corrieregiallorosso.com/corriere/totti-e-il-suo-marchio-di-fabbrica-tra-cucchiai-e-pallonetti-e-il-suo-colpo-preferito/|title=Totti e il suo \"marchio di fabbrica\": tra cucchiai e pallonetti \u00e8 il suo colpo preferito|publisher=Corriere GialloRosso|language=Italian|date=12 April 2011|accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n====2004\u20132009: Transition to striker====\nDespite Roma's disappointing [[2004\u201305 Serie A|2004\u201305 season]], which saw the departure of a number of players and several managerial changes,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldsoccer.com/uncategorized/serie-a-2004-05-team-by-team-guide-58070|title=Serie A 2004-05: Team by team guide|publisher=World Soccer|date=8 September 2004|accessdate=14 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asroma.com/en/news/2016/1/roma-world-no-4-thailand|title=Roma World No.4: Thailand|publisher=A.S. Roma|first=Paul|last=Rogers|date=7 January 2016|accessdate=14 November 2016}}</ref> Totti maintained consistent form by scoring 12 goals in Serie A,<ref name=legaseriea/> and 15 in all competitions, among which was his 100th Serie A goal from a free kick in a 3\u20133 draw against [[Inter Milan|Internazionale]], on 3 October 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/news/newsid=242306.html|title=Ton-up Totti rallies Roma|publisher=UEFA|date=3 October 2004|accessdate=27 July 2016}}</ref> Two months later, on 19 December, he became Roma's all-time [[A.S. Roma statistics and records#top|leading scorer in Serie A]] after netting his 107th career league goal against Parma, breaking the record previously held by [[Roberto Pruzzo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2004-12-20/totti-breaks-record-udinese-close-gap/605630|title=Totti breaks record, Udinese close gap|publisher=abc.net.au|date=19 December 2004|accessdate=27 July 2016}}</ref> Although Roma finished the league season in eighth place,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesi/ital05.html|title=Italy 2004/05|website=RSSSF|first1=Andrea|last1=Ferrigno|first2=Antonio|last2=Zea|date=26 July 2006|accessdate=14 November 2016}}</ref> Totti helped the team reach the [[2005 Coppa Italia Final|2005 Coppa Italia final]]; however Roma lost to Inter.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.repubblica.it/2006/04/sezioni/sport/calcio/semifinale-coppa-italia/semifinale-coppa-italia/semifinale-coppa-italia.html|title=Colpo Tommasi, Roma in finale Trover\u00e0 l'Inter, come nel 2005|work=la Repubblica|language=Italian|date=12 April 2006|accessdate=7 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nRoma's new coach for the [[2005\u201306 A.S. Roma season|2005\u201306 season]], [[Luciano Spalletti]], went with a [[Formation (association football)#4\u20133\u20132\u20131 (the \"Christmas Tree\" formation)|4\u20132\u20133\u20131 formation]], deploying Totti in a newer, more offensive role as a lone striker.<ref name=\"Never imagined being striker\"/> Despite his new attacking role, Totti usually dropped deep to pick up the ball in midfield rather than operating in the penalty area, thus creating space for the attacking midfielders and wingers to making offensive runs; the resulting system was later described as a [[Formation (association football)#4.E2.80.936.E2.80.930|4\u20136\u20130]], while Totti's particular attacking role was dubbed the \"[[Forward (association football)#False 9|false-9]]\".<ref name=\"Rome's greatest son\"/><ref name=\"great team tactics\">{{cite web|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/1435904-great-team-tactics-francesco-totti-roma-and-the-first-false-nine|title=Great Team Tactics: Francesco Totti, Roma and the First False Nine|website=Bleacher Report|first=Sam|last=Tighe|date=6 December 2012|accessdate=27 July 2016}}</ref> In this new position, Totti continued to score frequently, managing 15 goals in 24 league matches. In the spring of 2005, he renewed his contract until 2010, with an annual salary of \u20ac5.4&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2005/SPORT/football/05/31/italy.totti/|title=Totti agrees Roma deal extension|publisher=CNN|date=31 May 2005|accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref> On 19 February 2006, he suffered a fracture of his left [[fibula]] and ligament damage during a match against Empoli after being fouled by [[Richard Vanigli]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2006/feb/20/europeanfootball.sport1|title=Totti's broken ankle takes shine off Roma's 10th straight victory|work=The Guardian|date=20 February 2006|accessdate=31 May 2011}}</ref> Totti was at risk of missing the [[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006 World Cup]], but returned to the side on 11 May 2006 as a substitute in Roma's 3\u20131 [[2006 Coppa Italia Final|Coppa Italia final]] defeat to Inter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesi/italcup06.html |title=Italy Cup 2005/06 |website=RSSSF |first=Antonio |last=Zea |date=25 May 2006 |accessdate=7 January 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160207144448/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesi/italcup06.html |archivedate=7 February 2016 |df=dmy }}</ref> A metal plate had been attached to his ankle during surgery, but doctors decided not to operate again and remove it following Totti's return, concurring that the plate would not affect his game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribalfootball.com/articles/roma-doc-explains-totti-plate-decision-134941|title=Roma doc explains Totti plate decision|publisher=Tribal Football|date=17 June 2006 |accessdate=31 May 2011}}</ref> He was given [[Off-label use|off-label]] treatments of [[teriparatide]] to speed-up his fracture recovery.<ref name=\"Jancin\">{{cite web|url= http://www.internalmedicinenews.com/index.php?id=2049&type=98&tx_ttnews%5btt_news%5d=93933&cHash=da03e20e36 |title= Accelerating Fracture Healing With Teriparatide |first=Bruce |last=Jancin |publisher=Internal Medicine News Digital Network |date=12 December 2011|accessdate=20 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Coppa Italia 2008 premiazione.jpg|thumb|left|Totti lifts the [[2007\u201308 Coppa Italia]] trophy presented to him by President of Italy [[Giorgio Napolitano]] (right)]]\n\nThe [[2006\u201307 A.S. Roma season|2006\u201307 season]] was a personal high for Totti as he scored 26 goals in Serie A, as well as another six between the [[2006\u201307 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] (scoring three times in the group stage and once in the round of 16 tie against [[Olympique Lyonnais|Lyon]]) and the [[2006\u201307 Coppa Italia|Coppa Italia]], in addition to 15 assists in 50 games across all competitions.<ref name=\"Rome's greatest son\"/> Despite their elimination from the Champions League by [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] in the quarter-finals, and a second-place finish in the [[2006\u201307 Serie A|league]], Roma won the [[2007 Coppa Italia Final|Coppa Italia final]] against league champions Inter with a 6\u20132 victory at home (Totti scored the opening goal after 50 seconds) and a 2\u20131 defeat at the San Siro in [[Milan]].<ref name=\"Rome's greatest son\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/speciali/coppa_italia/2007/tabellini/142763.html|publisher=gazzetta.it|title=Coppa Italia Finale|date=9 May 2007|accessdate=27 July 2016|language=Italian}}</ref> Totti finished the season as [[Capocannonieri|Serie A top scorer]] with 26 goals,<ref name=\"Serie A Top Scorers\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesi/italtops.html |title=Italy&nbsp;\u2013 Serie A Top Scorers |website=RSSSF |first1=Roberto |last1=Di Maggio |first2=Igor |last2=Kramarsic |first3=Alberto |last3=Novello |date=11 June 2015 |accessdate=2 December 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151031163443/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesi/italtops.html |archivedate=31 October 2015 |df=dmy }}</ref> and on 17 June, he also received the [[European Sports Magazines|ESM]] [[European Golden Shoe]] award as the top European goalscorer of the season.<ref name=\"golden boot\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/6765029.stm|title=Totti scoops European Golden Boot|work=BBC Sport|date=18 June 2007|accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref> Despite being the highest active goalscorer in [[Serie A]], he was not among the finalists for the [[2007 FIFA World Player of the Year]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Primo_Piano/2007/10_Ottobre/10/fifa_world_player_1010.shtml|title=Ibra e Totti fuori dai 30|date=10 October 2007|accessdate=31 May 2011|work=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian}}</ref> due to his absence from the national team, although he was nominated for the [[2007 Ballon d'Or]], finishing tenth in the voting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/europa-poy07.html|title=European Footballer of the Year (\"Ballon d'Or\") 2007|website=RSSSF|accessdate=4 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 August 2007, Totti contributed to Roma's 1\u20130 victory over Inter in the [[2007 Supercoppa Italiana]], winning a penalty which was subsequently converted by [[Daniele De Rossi]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/SerieA/Squadre/Inter/Primo_Piano/2007/08_Agosto/19/supercoppa.shtml|title=La Supercoppa \u00e8 della Roma|work=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|first=Antonino|last=Morici|date=19 August 2007|accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref> Totti scored his 200th goal for Roma in a 4\u20130 victory against [[Torino F.C.|Torino]], in the [[2007\u201308 Coppa Italia|Coppa Italia]], on 16 January 2008.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.repubblica.it/2007/08/sezioni/sport/calcio/coppa-italia/ottavi-italia/ottavi-italia.html|title=Coppa Italia, il Catania elimina il Milan Totti 200 volte in gol e la Roma va|work=la Repubblica|language=Italian|date=16 January 2008|accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref> He was named the [[Serie A Italian Footballer of the Year]] for the fifth time in his career on 28 January.<ref name=\"Oscar-del-Calcio\"/> The following month, on 24 February, he reached 386 appearances in Serie A with Roma in a match against Fiorentina, equalling the club appearance record previously held by [[Giacomo Losi]], Roma's captain in the 1960s. He broke the record on 27 February, in the club's following league match against Inter.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/SerieA/Squadre/Inter/Primo_Piano/2008/02_Febbraio/27/intromcronaca.shtml|title=Totti illude la Roma Zanetti salva l'Inter|work=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|first=Antonino|last=Morici|date=27 February 2008|accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.repubblica.it/2008/03/sezioni/sport/calcio/serie_a/giornata-26a/roma-parma/roma-parma.html|title=Una Roma concreta ne segna 4 Il Parma si arrende a super Totti|work=la Repubblica|language=Italian|date=1 March 2008|accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref> On 9 March, he reached his 500th overall appearance for Roma, scoring the second goal of the match from a penalty kick in a 2\u20130 away win over Napoli.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2008/SPORT/football/03/09/football.italy/index.html|title=Totti spot on as Roma reel in leaders|publisher=CNN|date=9 March 2008|accessdate=26 June 2014}}</ref> Totti suffered a season-ending injury to his right knee during a 1\u20131 draw with [[A.S. Livorno Calcio|Livorno]] on 19 April. Tests revealed a tear of his [[anterior cruciate ligament]] (ACL) that required surgery, ruling him out for four months.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.channel4.com/sport/football_italia/apr20m.html|title=Totti 'ready in four months'\n|date=20 April 2008|accessdate=31 May 2011|publisher=Football Italia|language=}}</ref> Roma won their ninth [[2008 Coppa Italia Final|Coppa Italia]] with a 2\u20131 victory over Inter on 24 May; although Totti did not play the match, he was still allowed to lift the cup as the team's captain.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.repubblica.it/2007/08/sezioni/sport/calcio/coppa-italia/finale-partita/finale-partita.html|title=La Coppa Italia \u00e8 giallorossa \"Rivincita\" della Roma sull'Inter|work=la Repubblica|language=Italian|date=24 May 2008|accessdate=20 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/2008/05/25/coppa-italia-ancora-sua-prima-fischi-poi.html|title=Coppa Italia ancora sua prima fischi poi abbracci|work=la Repubblica|first=Fabrizio|last=Bocca|language=Italian|date=25 May 2008|accessdate=20 October 2015}}</ref> With this win, Totti became the most successful captain in the club's history, with five titles and ten runners-up medals.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.repubblica.it/sport/2016/04/21/news/dieci_numeri_carriera_totti-138100196/|title=Totti, 22 secondi per segnare 7900 giorni dopo il primo gol|work=la Repubblica|language=Italian|first=Matteo|last=Pinci|date=21 April 2016|accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Francesco Totti Vicario.JPG|230 px|thumb|right|Totti playing against [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]] in 2009 during the final year of Spalletti's first spell with Roma]]\n\nIn the [[2008\u201309 Serie A|2008\u201309 season]], Totti recovered from the previous injury, and took part in the [[2008 Supercoppa Italiana]] final on 24 August 2008; following a 2\u20132 draw with Inter after extra-time, Totti missed his penalty in the resulting shootout, which allowed [[Javier Zanetti]] to win the match for Inter with the following spot-kick.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/SerieA/Squadre/Inter/Primo_Piano/2008/08/24/partita.shtml|title=Inter, \u00e8 subito festa Supercoppa ai rigori|work=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|date=24 August 2008|accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref> On 8 November 2008, he made his 400th appearance in Serie A, in a 1\u20131 away draw against Bologna, scoring the opening goal of the match.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/SerieA/Squadre/Bologna/Primo_Piano/2008/11/08/bologna-roma.shtml|title=Roma, Totti non basta Mihajlovic: esordio con pari|work=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|first=Riccardo|last=Pratesi|date=8 November 2008|accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref> Later that month, he went on to help his team beat Lazio in the [[Derby della Capitale|Rome derby]], assisting [[J\u00falio Baptista]]'s match-winning goal.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.repubblica.it/2008/11/sezioni/sport/calcio/serie_a/giornata-12/roma-lazio/roma-lazio.html|title=Baptista fa respirare la Roma i giallorossi vincono il derby|work=la Repubblica|language=Italian|date=16 November 2008|accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref> Totti's run of good form continued as he provided assists for [[Mirko Vu\u010dini\u0107]] and scored a lobbed goal in a 3\u20130 win in a league game against [[U.S. Lecce|Lecce]] on 23 November,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldfootball.net/report/serie-a-2008-2009-us-lecce-as-roma/|title=US Lecce&nbsp;\u2013 AS Roma 0:3|publisher=worldfootball.net|date=23 November 2008|accessdate=9 June 2014}}</ref> while he netted a free kick in a 3\u20131 away win against [[CFR Cluj]] in the [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] later that week, on 27 November.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2009/matches/round=15276/match=302754/postmatch/report/index.html|title=Brighi double puts Roma in command|publisher=UEFA|first=Derek|last=Brookman|date=27 November 2008|accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref> He also scored the second goal in a 2\u20130 win against [[FC Girondins de Bordeaux|Bordeaux]] on 10 December, which ensured Roma's passage to the round of 16 of the competition as group winners.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2009/matches/round=15276/match=302778/postmatch/report/index.html|title=Totti clinches top spot for Roma|publisher=UEFA|date=10 December 2008|accessdate=25 June 2015}}</ref> On 19 April 2009, Totti scored his 175th Serie A goal in a 3\u20132 home win over Lecce, overtaking [[Amedeo Amadei]] as Roma's all-time highest goalscorer; with the goal, Totti also became one of the top-ten goalscorers in Serie A history.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/SerieA/Primo_Piano/2009/04/06/marcatori.shtml|title=Totti sale a quota 175 gol E' nella top ten di sempre|work=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|date=19 April 2009|accessdate=8 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n====2009\u20132011: Struggles and return to form====\nRoma's difficult start to the [[2008\u201309 A.S. Roma season|2008\u201309 season]] and continued struggles at the start of the [[2009\u201310 A.S. Roma season|2009\u201310 season]] saw Spalletti resign after his four-year reign and he was replaced by [[Claudio Ranieri]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/8231959.stm|title=Ranieri appointed new Roma coach|work=BBC Sport|date=2 September 2009|accessdate=2 September 2009|location=London}}</ref> Totti performed well in the inaugural [[UEFA Europa League]]; he scored two [[hat-tricks]] in the competition that season, first in a 7\u20131 away win against [[K.A.A. Gent|Gent]] in the [[2009\u201310 UEFA Europa League#Third qualifying round|third qualifying round]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://it.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/season=2010/matches/round=2000035/match=2000657/index.html|title=Gent 1\u20137 Roma|publisher=UEFA|language=Italian|date=6 August 2009|accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref> and then another in the same scoreline against [[MFK Ko\u0161ice]] at the Stadio Olimpico in the [[2009\u201310 UEFA Europa League#Play-off round|play-off round]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Roma d'autorit\u00e0, sette gol al Ko\u0161ice|url=http://it.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/season=2010/matches/round=2000036/match=2000738/index.html|publisher=UEFA|accessdate=29 July 2016|language=Italian|date=28 August 2009}}</ref> In Serie A, he also scored three goals against [[A.S. Bari|Bari]] on 22 November 2009, seven years on from his last hat-trick in Serie A.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportmediaset.mediaset.it/calcio/articoli/articolo28222.shtml|title=La Roma affonda il Bari, 3\u20131|publisher=Sport Mediaset|language=Italian|date=22 November 2009|accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://archiviostorico.gazzetta.it/2009/novembre/23/Totti_boom_Torna_minuti_ga_10_091123015.shtml|title=Totti boom Torna e ne fa 3 in 28 minuti|author=Ruggiero Palombo|newspaper=[[La Gazzetta dello Sport]]|date=November 23, 2009|language=italian}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/2009/11/23/totti-dicevano-che-ero-finito-meglio-cosi.html|title=Totti: Dicevano che ero finito Meglio cos\u00ec, mi porta bene|author=Francesca Ferrazza|newspaper=[[la Repubblica]]|date=November 23, 2009|page=4|language=italian}}</ref> Eight days later, Totti confirmed he had signed a new five-year playing contract which would see him at the club until 2014, after which he stated he would become a club director for a further five years.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.football-italia.net/dec1c.html |title=Totti finally signs new contract |date=1 December 2009 |accessdate=31 May 2011 |publisher=Football Italia |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091204154132/http://www.football-italia.net/dec1c.html |archivedate=4 December 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.football-italia.net/dec16q.html |title=Totti's Roma contract ratified |date=16 December 2009 |accessdate=31 May 2011 |publisher=Football Italia |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091219192930/http://www.football-italia.net/dec16q.html |archivedate=19 December 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref> Roma offered him an annual salary of \u20ac8.9&nbsp;million for 2009\u201310 and \u20ac8.6&nbsp;million a year for the next four seasons.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.asroma.it/pdf/corporate/operazioni_di_mercato/2009-12-16_prolungato_il_contratto_per_le_prestazioni_sportive_del_calciatore_francesco_totti.pdf|title=Prolungamento contratto economico di Francesco Totti|date=16 December 2009|accessdate=10 November 2012|publisher=AS Roma|language=Italian}}</ref>\n\nWith a 24-match unbeaten run in Serie A, Roma became the only challengers to Inter in the last three rounds for the league title that season,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldsoccer.com/news/ranieri-cautious-as-roma-go-top-296830|title=Ranieri cautious as Roma go top|publisher=World Soccer|date=12 April 2010|accessdate=27 April 2016}}</ref> ultimately finishing runners-up after the final game.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2010/may/16/inter-milan-win-serie-a|title=Internazionale take fifth successive Serie A title with win at Siena|work=The Guardian|date=16 May 2010|accessdate=27 April 2016}}</ref> Despite suffering several injury problems,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2010/mar/25/claudio-ranieri-roma-inter-serie-a|title=Claudio Ranieri the Roma revivalist aims to spoil another Milan party|work=The Guardian|first=Paolo|last=Bandini|date=25 March 2010|accessdate=2 August 2016}}</ref> he surpassed former prolific strikers such as Gabriel Batistuta,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tuttobari.com/curiosita/totti-aggancia-batigol-3552|title=Totti aggancia Batigol|publisher=Tutto Bari|language=Italian|first=Michele|last=Lorusso|date=5 October 2009|accessdate=2 August 2016}}</ref> [[Giuseppe Signori]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laroma24.it/rubriche/la-penna-degli-altri/2010/01/totti-fa-188-e-raggiunge-signori|title=Totti fa 188 e raggiunge Signori|publisher=La Roma 24|language=Italian|date=24 January 2010|accessdate=2 August 2016}}</ref> and [[Kurt Hamrin]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://it.eurosport.com/calcio/serie-a/2009-2010/totti-ci-siamo_sto2311142/story.shtml|title=Totti \"Ci siamo e ci saremo fino alla fine\"|publisher=Eurosport|language=Italian|accessdate=2 August 2016}}</ref> putting him in sixth place in the all-time Serie A scoring records.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laroma24.it/approfondimenti/approfondimenti-approfondimenti/2011/03/totti-ecco-i-numeri-aggiornati-254-gol-con-la-maglia-della-roma-199-in-serie-a-e-8-nei-derby|title=Totti, ecco i numeri aggiornati: 254 gol con la maglia della Roma, 199 in Serie A e 8 nei derby|publisher=La Roma 24|language=Italian|date=13 March 2011|accessdate=2 August 2016}}</ref> Totti also played in the [[2010 Coppa Italia Final|Coppa Italia final]] against Inter on 5 May 2010, but received a red card in the closing minutes of the second half for kicking [[Mario Balotelli]]; Roma lost the match 0\u20131, thus failing to bring home a record tenth Coppa Italia title.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.us/story/783535/francesco-totti-rejects-mario-balotellis-racism-claim|title=Totti rejects Balotelli's racism claim|publisher=ESPN FC|date=8 May 2010|accessdate=27 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Totti 2011 crop.jpg|thumb|308x308px|Totti in 2011|alt=]]\n\nIn the [[2010\u201311 A.S. Roma season|2010\u201311 season]], Roma suffered yet another defeat to Inter in the [[2010 Supercoppa Italiana]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/SerieA/Inter/21-08-2010/supercoppa-roma-spreca-71864477191.shtml|title=Supercoppa, la Roma spreca Eto'o la punisce: 3\u20131 Inter|trans-title=Supercup, Roma waste Eto'o punishes them|work=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|first=Riccardo|last=Pratesi|date=21 August 2010|accessdate=27 April 2016}}</ref> continuing their \"traditional\" early struggles, which Totti partly blamed on Ranieri's defensive mindset and failure to develop a consistent set of tactics.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/european/roma-coach-ranieri-dismisses-totti-row-2091964.html|title=Roma coach Ranieri dismisses Totti row|work=[[The Independent]]|date=28 September 2010|accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/fifa-world-ranking/news/y=2010/m=9/news=catania-lie-wait-for-high-flying-cesena-1305144.html|title=Catania lie in wait for high-flying Cesena|publisher=FIFA|date=21 September 2010|accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/3276/serie-a/2010/09/18/2124860/roma-coach-claudio-ranieri-defends-his-team-and-francesco|title=Roma coach Claudio Ranieri defends his team and Francesco Totti|publisher=Goal.com|first=Serafino|last=Ingardia|date=18 September 2010|accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Low morale in Roma camp\">{{cite web|url=http://www.football-italia.net/node/1097|title=Low morale in Roma camp|publisher=Football Italia|accessdate=29 July 2016|date=6 December 2010}}</ref> On a personal level, Totti won the [[Golden Foot]] award,<ref name=\"ESPN.co.uk\">{{cite web|title=Roma star Totti awarded Golden Foot prize|url=http://espnfc.com/news/story?id=831489|accessdate=15 April 2014|publisher=ESPN FC|date=11 October 2010}}</ref> but Ranieri's lack of faith in him due to his age meant that the captain would spend a lot of time on the substitute's bench in favour of younger forwards, such as [[Marco Borriello]], Mirko Vu\u010dini\u0107 and [[J\u00e9r\u00e9my M\u00e9nez]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.corrieredellosport.it/serie_a/roma/2010/11/23-140751/Totti+escluso+col+Bayern.+Spazio+a+Vucinic-Borriello|title=Roma con Vucinic-Borriello Milan, Ronaldinho fuori|work=Corriere dello Sport|language=Italian|first=Guido|last=D'Ubaldo|date=23 November 2010|accessdate=29 July 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160821003907/http://www.corrieredellosport.it/serie_a/roma/2010/11/23-140751/Totti+escluso+col+Bayern.+Spazio+a+Vucinic-Borriello|archivedate=21 August 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.football-italia.net/node/1866|title=Ranieri: 'Totti at the centre of my Roma'|publisher=Football Italia|date=8 January 2011|accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref> His limited playing time, which included a controversial 91st minute substitution in a 2\u20131 away loss against Sampdoria,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.legaseriea.it/it/serie-a-tim/match-report/-/match-report/Sampdoria-Roma/25604 |title=Sampdoria-Roma Official Match Report |publisher=Lega Serie A |language=Italian |date=9 January 2011 |accessdate=31 May 2011 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120722083953/http://www.legaseriea.it/it/serie-a-tim/match-report/-/match-report/Sampdoria-Roma/25604 |archivedate=22 July 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> resulted in several clashes with Ranieri, and saw him fall out of form, scoring only three league goals in 21 appearances;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.football-italia.net/node/2756|title=Totti tantrums|publisher=Football Italia|first=Dave|last=Taylor|date=16 January 2011|accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref> as a result of his limited appearances, despondence and strenuous relationship with the manager, rumours even circulated in the media that Totti was considering leaving Roma.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.football-italia.net/node/1940|title=Totti confirms: 'I am sad at Roma'|publisher=Football Italia|date=11 January 2011|accessdate=30 July 2016}}</ref> Following Roma's 4\u20133 loss against [[Genoa C.F.C.|Genoa]] on 20 February 2011, Ranieri resigned as manager of Roma, and Totti saw his former teammate Vincenzo Montella appointed as caretaker coach.<ref name=\"roma-resigned\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/9403122.stm|title=Claudio Ranieri resigns as coach of Serie A side Roma |date=20 February 2011|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=20 February 2011 }}</ref>\n\nMontella reverted to Spalletti's 4\u20132\u20133\u20131 system and Totti appeared to recapture his best form, finding the net more frequently towards the end of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/it/news/2/serie-a/2011/02/22/2363519/la-roma-di-montella-nasce-con-unimportante-scelta-totti|title=La Roma di Montella nasce con un'importante scelta: Totti centravanti e Borriello in panchina!|publisher=Goal.com|language=Italian|date=22 February 2011|accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Who is Roma's Player of the Season?\">{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/1717/editorial/2011/05/11/2479366/who-is-romas-player-of-the-season|title=Who is Roma's Player of the Season?|publisher=Goal.com|date=11 May 2011|accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref> On 3 March, Totti was voted the best active Italian player in a poll conducted by ''[[La Gazzetta dello Sport]]''; 100 Italian personalities including footballers, politicians and celebrities took part in the vote. On 13 March 2011, he scored two goals against Lazio which gave Roma their fifth consecutive victory in the Rome Derby.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/SerieA/Roma/13-03-2011/derby-totti-festa-roma-80471159660.shtml|title=Il derby di Totti, festa Roma! Lazio al tappeto: finisce 2\u20130|work=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|date=13 March 2011|accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref> The following match, on 20 March, Totti became the sixth player in Serie A history to score 200 goals, finding the target twice in a 2\u20132 draw against Fiorentina to total 201 league goals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/soccer/roma-s-totti-tops-200-career-goals-serie-a-1.1036503|title=Roma's Totti tops 200 career goals: Serie A|publisher=CBC Sports|date=20 March 2011|accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref> On 1 May, Totti scored a brace against Bari to equal and subsequently overtake [[Roberto Baggio]] as the fifth-highest goalscorer in Serie A with his 205th and 206th career league goals, putting him behind only [[Silvio Piola]], [[Gunnar Nordahl]], [[Giuseppe Meazza]] and [[Jos\u00e9 Altafini]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/clubfootball/news/newsid=1427782.html|title=Totti crowned modern goal-scoring king|publisher=FIFA|date=1 May 2011|accessdate=31 May 2011}}</ref> Totti ended the [[2010\u201311 Serie A]] campaign with 15 goals&nbsp;\u2013 with twelve of his goals coming in Roma's last 13 league fixtures.<ref name=\"Who is Roma's Player of the Season?\"/>\n\nAt the end of the season, Roma underwent a change of ownership, with the former club owner [[Rosella Sensi]] being replaced by an American consortium led by [[Thomas R. DiBenedetto|Thomas DiBenedetto]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://asia.eurosport.com/football/serie-a/2010-2011/roma-takeover-completed_sto2912296/story.shtml|title=DiBenedetto finally seals Roma takeover|publisher=Eurosport.com|date=18 August 2011|accessdate=10 September 2012}}</ref> Under the new management, the club did not offer a permanent contract to Montella, which led to him leaving to coach another Serie A side, [[Calcio Catania|Catania]].<ref name=\"montella_catania\">{{cite news|url=http://www.calciocatania.it/comunicati/comunicati.php?id=23140 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727110006/http://www.calciocatania.it/comunicati/comunicati.php?id=23140 |archivedate=27 July 2011 |title=Vincenzo Montella \u00e8 il nuovo allenatore del Catania \u2013 Venerd\u00ec 10 giugno alle 16.30 la presentazione |publisher=Calcio Catania |date=9 June 2011 |accessdate=4 December 2013 |language=Italian |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> The Roma management appointed [[Luis Enrique (footballer)|Luis Enrique]], who had previous coached the [[FC Barcelona B|Barcelona B]] side, in a bid to emulate [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]]'s football style.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.zonalmarking.net/2011/12/14/luis-enrique-roma-tactics-barcelona/|title=How effectively is Luis Enrique implementing the Barcelona methods at Roma?|publisher=Zonal Marking|date=14 December 2011|accessdate=10 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n====2011\u20132012: Back to playmaker====\nThe [[2011\u201312 A.S. Roma season|2011\u201312 season]] saw Totti initially receive few starts under Roma's new manager Luis Enrique, as the club's early struggles continued.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/1717/editorial/2011/08/20/2628008/whether-luis-enrique-is-right-or-wrong-francesco-totti-must-back-|title=Whether Luis Enrique is right or wrong, Francesco Totti must back him for the good of Roma|publisher=Goal.com|date=20 August 2011|accessdate=28 June 2014}}</ref> Totti sustained an injury on 1 October 2011 in the second half of a match against [[Atalanta B.C.|Atalanta]], which kept him out of action until the 20 November;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://au.eurosport.com/football/serie-a/2011-2012/totti-doubt-for-rome-derby_sto2975541/story.shtml|title=Totti doubt for Rome derby|publisher=Eurosport|date=4 October 2011|accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref> he returned to the pitch against Lecce, when he came off the bench in the 66th minute, as Roma won the match 2\u20131.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en/match/roma-vs-lecce/1175738/report|title=Roma 2\u20131 Lecce: Pjanic and Gago ensure wasteful Giallorossi hang on for narrow win|publisher=Goal.com|first=Livio|last=Caferoglu|date=20 November 2011|accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn mid-December, as Totti began regaining form post-injury, he started playing more regularly, often in a creative role as an attacking midfielder. On 12 December, he set up Daniele De Rossi's opening goal in a 1\u20131 home draw against eventual league champions Juventus, although Totti missed a second-half penalty during the match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/10/italy/2011/12/14/2802126/juventus-gianluigi-buffon-saving-francesco-tottis-penalty|title=Juventus' Gianluigi Buffon: Saving Francesco Totti's penalty against Roma was down to hard work in training|publisher=Goal.com|date=14 December 2011|accessdate=17 January 2012}}</ref> He provided several more assists that season, notably for [[Dani Osvaldo]]'s goal in Roma's 3\u20131 win over Napoli at the [[Stadio San Paolo]] on 18 December 2011,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Squadre/Napoli/18-12-2011/roma-espugna-san-paolo-aggancia-napoli-quota-21--804067721759.shtml|title=La Roma si scopre pratica 1\u20133 al Napoli e aggancio|work=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|first=Livia|last=Taglioli|date=18 December 2011|accessdate=30 July 2016}}</ref> and also set up De Rossi's goal against Catania at the Massimino stadium.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Squadre/Catania/14-01-2012/legrottaglie-de-rossi-poi-pioggiacatania-roma-sospesa-1-1-65--818642441.shtml|title=Legrottaglie-De Rossi, poi la pioggia Catania-Roma sospesa sull'1\u20131 al 65'|work=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|first=Emiliano|last=Pozzoni|date=14 January 2012|accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref> Playing in a deeper position on the pitch, the Roma talisman did not seek to score goals as often, opting rather to play more of a supporting role by bridging the gap between attack and midfield, using his presence, leadership and experience in games to offer some much needed depth to the team.<ref name=\"Rome's greatest son\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/blog/2011/dec/14/guardian-sport-network-luis-enrique|title=How well is Luis Enrique implementing the Barcelona methods at Roma?|work=The Guardian|first=Michael|last=Cox|date=14 December 2011|accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.corrieredellosport.it/serie_a/roma/2011/09/21-194567/Luis+Enrique%3A+%C2%ABStiamo+bene.+Serve+solo+una+vittoria%C2%BB|title=Luis Enrique: \"Stiamo bene. Serve solo una vittoria\"|work=Corriere dello Sport|language=Italian|first=Valerio|last=Minutiello|date=21 September 2011|accessdate=29 July 2016}}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.repubblica.it/sport/calcio/serie-a/roma/2012/04/17/news/totti_leader_verso_juventus-33479235/|title=Luis Enrique si affida a Totti \"L'unico che mi d\u00e0 una mano\"|work=la Repubblica|language=Italian|first=Matteo|last=Pinci|date=17 April 2012|accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 January 2012, Totti scored his first goals of the season in a 2\u20130 win against [[A.C. Chievo Verona|Chievo]], converting one penalty in the first half and another in the second.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/match/roma-vs-chievo/1175787/report|title=Roma 2\u20130 Chievo: Totti nets twice from the spot as Luis Enrique's men move into top six in Serie A|publisher=Goal.com|first=Enis|last=Koylu|date=8 January 2012|accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref> He went on to score two goals in a 5\u20131 win against [[A.C. Cesena|Cesena]] which allowed Totti to set a new record, as his second goal of the match brought his tally to 211 league goals&nbsp;\u2013 the most any player has ever scored for a single club in Serie A.<ref name=\"Totti sets Serie A scoring record as Roma run riot\">{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2012/01/21/sport/football/italy-spain-totti/index.html|title=Totti sets Serie A scoring record as Roma run riot|publisher=CNN|date=22 January 2012|accessdate=28 June 2014}}</ref> Despite his inability to find the back of the net as the second half of the season began, he continued to perform well, as he notably assisted [[Juan (footballer)|Juan]]'s goal from a corner in Roma's 4\u20130 win over Inter on 5 February.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.football-italia.net/SerieA/match/9784|title=Roma 4&nbsp;\u2013 0 Inter|publisher=Football Italia|date=5 February 2012|accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref> On 12 April, Totti scored his fifth goal of the season in a 3\u20131 victory over Udinese.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/del-piero-and-totti-grab-perfect-wave-big-wednesday-serie|title=Del Piero and Totti grab the perfect wave on Big Wednesday in Serie A|magazine=FourFourTwo|date=12 April 2012|accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref> He scored again in a 2\u20131 loss against Fiorentina on 25 April,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.calciomercato.com/news/roma-fiorentina-1-2-il-tabellino-869967|title=Roma-Fiorentina 1\u20132: Il tabellino|publisher=Calciomercato.com|language=Italian|date=25 April 2012|accessdate=29 April 2016}}</ref> and two weeks later, on his 500th match in Serie A, he scored two goals in a 2\u20132 draw against Catania at the Stadio Olimpico.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.football-italia.net/SerieA/match/9932|title=Roma 2&nbsp;\u2013 2|publisher=Football Italia|date=5 May 2012|accessdate=27 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n====2012\u20132013: Breaking records====\n[[File:Francesco Totti.jpg|180px|thumbnail|left|Totti in action during a 2012 friendly match against [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] in Boston, Massachusetts]]\n\nAfter Luis Enrique decided to resign due to an unsuccessful season in which Roma failed to qualify for European football for the first time in 15 years, the club decided to appoint their former manager [[Zden\u011bk Zeman]], with whom Totti would once again be reunited. Zeman tried to play Totti in a free role as a left forward or winger in his preferred 4\u20133\u20133 tactical line-up.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.corrieredellosport.it/serie_a/roma/2012/09/04-263175/Roma,+ecco+il+4-3-Totti-2%3A+il+nuovo+modulo+di+Zeman|title=Roma, ecco il 4-3-Totti-2: il nuovo modulo di Zeman|trans-title=Roma, here is the 4-3-Totti-2: Zeman's new formation|work=Corriere dello Sport|language=Italian|last1=Maida|first1=Roberto|date=4 September 2012|accessdate=9 March 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402091847/http://www.corrieredellosport.it/serie_a/roma/2012/09/04-263175/Roma,+ecco+il+4-3-Totti-2%3A+il+nuovo+modulo+di+Zeman|archivedate=2 April 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Although this was a similar role to that which he had played during Zeman's previous spell 13 years before, Totti's freedom also enabled him to drop deep into the midfield to press opponents and pick up the ball, as well as attacking on the left wing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/it/news/2/serie-a/2012/06/04/3147225/lamela-come-totti-con-zeman-si-torna-al-1997-quando-totti|title=Lamela come Totti: con Zeman si torna al 1997, quando Totti ricamava all'ala. 'Coco' pu\u00f2 diventare nuovo idolo della sinistra|trans-title=Lamela like Totti: Zeman returns to his 1997 system, when Totti played as a winger. 'Coco' can become the new idol on the left|publisher=Goal.com|language=Italian|date=4 June 2012|accessdate=9 March 2015}}</ref> On 2 September, Totti provided 2 assists for [[Alessandro Florenzi]] and Dani Osvaldo in Roma's 3\u20131 win over Inter at the San Siro. After the match, he received praise from the media due to his performance, even as he approached his 36th birthday.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.football-italia.net/24649/fantasy-totti-and-gio|title=The fantasy of Totti and Gio|date=3 September 2012|accessdate=10 September 2012|publisher=Football Italia|language=}}</ref> On 21 October, Totti surpassed both Giuseppe Meazza and Jos\u00e9 Altafini's joint-record after scoring the first of Roma's goals in a 4\u20132 away win at Genoa, becoming the third-highest scorer in Serie A history with 217 goals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com/soccer/story/genoa-2-4-roma-serie-a-totti-milestone-match-report-102112|title=Totti gets milestone goal in Roma win|publisher=Fox Sports Soccer|date=21 October 2012|accessdate=2 August 2016}}</ref> On 8 December, Totti scored two goals, his fifth and sixth of the season, in a 4\u20132 home victory against Fiorentina.<ref name=\"SB Nation\">{{cite news|url=https://www.sbnation.com/soccer/2012/12/8/3744810/roma-v-fiorentina-final-score-goals-report|title=Roma v Fiorentina, final score 4\u20132: Francesco Totti keeps Roma flying high|work=SB Nation|first=Kirsten|last=Schlewitz|date=8 December 2012|accessdate=13 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the club's negative performances, Zeman was sacked and replaced by the club's technique coach [[Aurelio Andreazzoli]] in early February 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.football-italia.net/30269/official-roma-sack-zeman|title=OFFICIAL: ROMA SACK ZEMAN|publisher=Football Italia|date=2 February 2013|accessdate=27 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/3276/serie-a/2013/02/05/3728223/zeman-not-bitter-about-roma-sacking?ICID=AR_HL_2|title=Zeman not bitter about Roma sacking|publisher=Goal.com|first=Henry|last=Jackson|date=5 February 2013|accessdate=23 April 2013}}</ref> Under his new manager, Totti scored a goal against Juventus on 16 February, with a powerful strike, as Roma shocked the league leaders in a 1\u20130 win.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en/match/roma-vs-juventus/1351496/report|title=Roma 1\u20130 Juventus: Champions shocked by Totti thunderbolt|publisher=Goal.com|first=Mark|last=Doyle|date=16 February 2013|accessdate=25 July 2013}}</ref> On 3 March, he scored his 225th goal against Genoa to become Serie A's joint second-top scorer \u2013 alongside Gunnar Nordahl \u2013 as Roma cruised to a 3\u20131 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espnfc.com/us/en/report/351821/report.html |title=AS Roma 3\u20131 Genoa |publisher=ESPN FC |date=3 March 2013 }}</ref> Totti finally broke Nordahl's record by scoring against Parma on 18 March, increasing his Serie A tally to 226 goals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laroma24.it/rubriche/la-penna-degli-altri/2013/03/totti-su-punizione-20-di-gloria/|title=Totti su punizione: 20 di gloria|trans-title=Totti from a free-kick: 20 glorious goals|publisher=LaRoma24.it|language=Italian|date=19 March 2013|accessdate=9 March 2015}}</ref> On 8 April, with a goal from a penalty kick in the 1\u20131 draw against Lazio, he became the joint top scorer of all time in Serie A in the Rome Derby with nine goals, putting him on par with [[Dino da Costa]] and [[Marco Delvecchio]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Squadre/Roma/08-04-2013/roma-lazio-1-1-totti-riacciuffa-hernanes-92892757459.shtml|title=Roma-Lazio 1\u20131, Totti l'uomo dei record riacciuffa Hernanes|trans-title=Roma-Lazio 1\u20131, Totti the recordman catches Hernanes|work=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|last1=Nicita|first1=Maurizio|date=8 April 2013|accessdate=9 March 2015}}</ref> Totti finished the [[2012\u201313 Serie A]] season with 12 goals and 12 assists from 34 appearances.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://forzaitalianfootball.com/2013/05/serie-a-team-of-the-season-201213/|title=Serie A Team Of The Season 2012/13|publisher=Forza Italian Football|first=Sam|last=Lewis|date=20 May 2013|accessdate=9 March 2015}}</ref> Totti also reached the [[2013 Coppa Italia Final|2013 Coppa Italia final]] with Roma, but lost the match 0\u20131 on 26 May to cross-city rivals Lazio.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/22676789|title=Lazio beat rivals Roma in Coppa Italia final|work=BBC Sport|date=26 May 2013|accessdate=6 June 2013 }}</ref>\n\n====2013\u20132015: Free forward====\nWith the arrival of Roma's new coach [[Rudi Garcia]] in the summer of 2013, Totti was once again deployed as a [[False 9|false-9]], while also functioning as a supporting forward, or as winger on the left on occasion.<ref name=\"Rome's greatest son\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ilprimatonazionale.it/primo-piano/francesco-totti-la-versione-inimitabile-del-falso-nueve-9818/|title=Francesco Totti: la versione inimitabile del \"falso nueve\"|publisher=Il Primato Nazionale|language=Italian|date=18 September 2014|accessdate=25 June 2015}}</ref> On 20 September 2013, Roma announced that Totti had signed a new contract, keeping him at the club until 2016, past his 39th birthday.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espnfc.com/news/story/_/id/1558451/roma-icon-francesco-totti-pens-new-deal-2016|title=Roma icon Totti pens new deal to 2016|date=20 September 2013|accessdate=20 September 2013|publisher=ESPN FC}}</ref> He scored his first goal of the [[2013\u201314 A.S. Roma season|2013\u201314 season]] on 16 September, against Parma in a 3\u20131 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/parma-vs-roma/301570|title=Parma vs. Roma (1\u20133)|publisher=Sky Sports|date=16 September 2013|accessdate=17 August 2016}}</ref> He followed up the goal with two strikes in Roma's 3\u20130 away victory over Inter, helping the team maintain a 100% record after seven games.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2013/oct/07/roma-resurrection-francesco-totti-serie-a|title=Roma's resurrection embodied by Francesco Totti&nbsp;\u2013 sparked by Garcia|work=The Guardian|date=7 October 2013|accessdate=28 December 2014}}</ref> On 20 November, he received the \"Captain of Captains\" award by the association Editutto and Baker Tilly Revisa.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.corrieredellosport.it/serie_a/roma/2013/11/20341623/Serie+A+Roma,+Totti+riceve+il+premio+%22Capitano+dei+capitani%22|title=Serie A Roma, Totti riceve il premio \"Capitano dei capitani\"|work=Corriere dello Sport|language=Italian|date=20 November 2013|accessdate=8 January 2014}}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n[[File:CSKA-Roma (7).jpg|thumbnail|left|180px|Totti in 2014 playing for Roma against [[PFC CSKA Moscow|CSKA Moscow]] in the [[UEFA Champions League]]]]\n\nOn 14 February, Totti was sidelined for about a month after sustaining a bruised right buttock.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.repubblica.it/sport/calcio/serie-a/roma/2014/02/14/news/confermata_chiusura_curca_roma-78599204/|title=Roma, confermata la chiusura delle curve. E Totti si ferma per la Samp|work=la Repubblica|language=Italian|date=14 February 2014|accessdate=2 August 2016}}</ref> He returned to the pitch on 17 March against Udinese, scoring the first goal of the match as he helped his team to a 3\u20132 win.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/26618546|title=Francesco Totti scored on his return as Roma beat Udinese to maintain their grip on second place in Serie A.|work=BBC Sport|date=17 March 2014|accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref> Eight days later, Totti celebrated 700 overall appearances with Roma against [[Torino F.C.|Torino]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.football-italia.net/SerieA/match/37278|title=Roma 2 \u2013 1 Torino|publisher=Football Italia|date=25 March 2014|accessdate=17 August 2016}}</ref> On 2 April, he scored his 20th career goal against Parma (a personal record against any side) in a 4\u20132 victory.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/26714335|title=Francesco Totti scored a superb goal as Roma beat Parma to move eight points behind Serie A leaders Juventus with seven games remaining|work=BBC Sport|date=2 April 2014|accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref> He finished the season with eight goals and ten assists, ending the year as the top assist provider of the [[2013\u201314 Serie A]] season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/italian-serie-a/12/statistics/assists|title=Italian Serie A Stats: Assists Leaders&nbsp;\u2013 2013\u201314|publisher=ESPN FC|accessdate=29 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nPrior to the start of the [[2014\u201315 A.S. Roma season|2014\u201315 season]], Totti had been one of the star players of Roma's pre-season friendlies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laroma24.it/rubriche/la-penna-degli-altri/2014/08/precampionato-giallorosso-totti-capocannoniere-florenzi-e-astori-i-piu-schierati/|title=Precampionato giallorosso, Totti capocannoniere. Florenzi e Astori i pi\u00f9 schierati|publisher=LaRoma24.it|date=28 August 2014|accessdate=15 June 2015|language=Italian}}</ref>\nOn 30 September 2014, three days after his 38th birthday, Totti scored Roma's equaliser in a Champions League group stage draw at [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]], thus becoming the oldest scorer in the history of the competition;<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/29362609|title=Man City 1\u20131 Roma|work=BBC Sport|last=McNulty|first=Phil|date=30 September 2014|accessdate=30 September 2014}}</ref> it was also Totti's 300th professional career goal.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/competitions/champions-league/11132270/Francesco-Totti-reigns-supreme-with-sublime-equaliser-against-Manchester-City-in-the-Champions-League.html|title=Manchester City left red-faced following unfortunate tweet as Francesco Totti reigns supreme with sublime equaliser|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|first=Mark|last=Ogden|date=30 September 2014|accessdate=2 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/goal-of-the-week/winners-showcase/|title=WINNERS SHOWCASE|publisher=UEFA|accessdate=25 June 2015}}</ref> On 25 October, Totti scored the opening goal from a free kick in a 1\u20131 draw against [[PFC CSKA Moscow|CSKA Moscow]], extending his record of oldest goalscorer in the history of the competition to 38 years and 59 days.<ref name=\"UCL Record\">{{cite web|url=http://metro.co.uk/2014/11/25/francesco-totti-breaks-own-record-to-become-oldest-goalscorer-in-champions-league-with-roma-goal-4962893/|title=Francesco Totti breaks OWN record to become oldest goalscorer in Champions League with Roma strike|publisher=Metro|date=25 November 2014|accessdate=26 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 January 2015, Totti scored two goals against local rivals Lazio, making him the joint all-time top scorer in the Rome Derby in official club competitions, alongside Dino Da Costa, with 11 goals, as well as the Serie A top scorer in the Rome Derby.<ref name=\"Roma vs. Lazio: 2-2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/30719796|title=Roma vs. Lazio: 2\u20132|publisher=BBC.com|accessdate=12 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Totti da record\">{{cite web|url=http://www.panorama.it/sport/calcio/totti-record-manca-gol-per-essere-re-dei-derby|title=Totti da record, manca un gol per essere il Re dei derby|trans-title=Record-breaking Totti, he only needs a goal to be the King of the Rome derby|publisher=Panorama|language=Italian|last1=Politan\u00f2|first1=Matteo|date=12 January 2015|accessdate=9 March 2015}}</ref> On 9 May, Totti scored from a penalty in a 2\u20131 away defeat to Milan, equalling Roberto Baggio for the [[Football records in Italy#Most goals from a penalty kick|record of the most goals scored in Serie A from penalties]] (68).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Serie-A/Milan/09-05-2015/serie-a-milan-roma-2-1-decisivo-ex-destro-non-basta-totti-110754214922.shtml|title=Milan-Roma 2\u20131: decisivo l'ex Destro|trans-title=Milan-Roma 2\u20131: Destro, the decisive ex|work=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|first=Marco|last=Fallisi|date=9 May 2015|accessdate=11 May 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Did you know\">{{cite web|url=http://www.football-italia.net/66346/serie-week-35-did-you-know|title=Serie A Week 35: Did You Know?|publisher=Football Italia|date=12 May 2015|accessdate=23 December 2015}}</ref> On 31 May, in the final match-day of the [[2014\u201315 Serie A|2014\u201315 season]], he scored his 299th goal for Roma in a 2\u20131 home defeat to [[U.S. Citt\u00e0 di Palermo|Palermo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.forzaroma.info/2015/05/31/per-totti-i-gol-roma-299/442639|title=Totti: \"I miei gol? Sono ancora 299\"&nbsp;\u2013 VIDEO|publisher=ForzaRoma.info|accessdate=2 June 2015|date=31 May 2015}}</ref> Totti finished the season as Roma's leading scorer with ten goals in all competitions, the seventh time in which he had been the team's top scorer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asroma.it/en/news/fulltime_roma_v_palermo/|title=ROMA 1\u20132 PALERMO, FULLTIME No. 50|publisher=A.S. Roma|date=1 June 2015|accessdate=4 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n====2015\u20132017: Final years as a super sub====\nOn his second league appearance of the [[2015\u201316 Serie A]] season, Totti scored his 300th career club goal in all competitions with Roma in a 2\u20132 home draw with [[U.S. Sassuolo Calcio|Sassuolo]], on 20 September 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=2273554.html|title=Why do Roma fans love Francesco Totti?|publisher=UEFA|first=Paolo|last=Menicucci|date=20 September 2015|accessdate=20 September 2015}}</ref> On 26 September 2015, the day before his 39th birthday, he sustained an injury, straining his right hip flexor in a 5\u20131 win over [[Carpi F.C. 1909|Carpi]], ruling him out for three months.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/as-roma/story/2634474/roma-duo-francesco-totti-and-edin-dzeko-out-for-four-weeks|title=Roma duo Francesco Totti and Edin Dzeko sidelined for four weeks|publisher=ESPN FC|date=27 September 2015|accessdate=27 September 2015}}</ref> He returned to the pitch as a substitute in a 1\u20131 home draw against Milan, on 9 January 2016,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tsn.ca/ac-milan-draws-at-roma-1.420579|title=AC Milan draws at Roma|publisher=TSN|date=9 January 2016|accessdate=11 January 2016}}</ref> equalling [[Gianluca Pagliuca]] as the [[Football records in Italy#Appearances|third all-time highest appearance holder in Serie A history]], with 592 appearances.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/club/as-roma/104/blog/post/2783927/as-roma-second-half-capitulation-indicative-of-poor-season|title=AS Roma's second-half capitulation vs. Milan indicative of poor season so far|publisher=ESPN FC|first=Terry|last=Daley|date=10 January 2016|accessdate=11 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 February 2016, Totti publicly criticised returning manager \u2013 and Rudi Garcia's replacement \u2013 Luciano Spalletti in the media for his lack of playing time since his return from injury. He was subsequently dropped for Roma's 5\u20130 win over Palermo, with the decision causing an uproar among the fans and in the media,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/club/as-roma/104/blog/post/2812892/francesco-totti-faces-uncertain-roma-future|title=Francesco Totti faces uncertain Roma future after controversial comments|publisher=ESPN FC|first=Terry|last=Daley|date=22 February 2016|accessdate=23 February 2016}}</ref> while rumours once again began to circulate that Totti would be leaving the club once his contract had expired at the end of the season, as a result of his limited appearances and clashes with Spalletti.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/723/serie-a/2016/02/20/20556722/totti-admits-he-is-considering-roma-exit|title=Totti admits he is considering Roma exit|publisher=Goal.com|first=Jamie|last=Smith|date=20 February 2016|accessdate=30 July 2016}}</ref> On 8 March, Totti came on as a substitute for [[Stephan El Shaarawy]] in the return leg of the round of 16 of the [[2015\u201316 UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League]] against Real Madrid, and was given a standing ovation by the fans at the Santiago Bernab\u00e9u Stadium in Madrid; Roma lost the match 2\u20130, however, and were eliminated from the competition following a 4\u20130 aggregate loss.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/as-roma/story/2825492/roma-striker-francesco-totti-overwhelmed-by-bernabeu-ovation|title=Roma striker Francesco Totti overwhelmed by Bernabeu ovation|publisher=ESPN FC|first=Ben|last=Gladwell|date=9 March 2016|accessdate=9 March 2016}}</ref> On 20 April, he came off the bench in the 86th minute, one goal down to Torino at home to rescue the team with a brace; one in the 87th minute and a penalty in the 89th minute to win the match 3\u20132.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.us/club/as-roma/104/blog/post/2855212/francesco-totti-rescues-roma-with-miracle-brace-vs-torino|title=Francesco Totti's late rescue gives Roma miracle win vs. Torino|publisher=ESPN FC|first=Terry|last=Daley|date=20 April 2016|accessdate=21 April 2016}}</ref> With his 69th goal in Serie A from the penalty spot, he overtook Roberto Baggio as the outright top scorer of penalties in Serie A history.<ref name=rigore>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/it/news/2/serie-a/2016/04/22/22675912/totti-riscrive-la-storia-baggio-superato-sui-calci-di-rigore|title=Totti riscrive la storia: Baggio superato sui calci di rigore, Higuain per media-goal|trans-title=Totti rewrites history: Baggio overtaken on penalties, Higuain in terms of goalscoring average|publisher=Goal.com|language=Italian|date=22 April 2016|accessdate=25 April 2016}}</ref> Totti's double also made him the oldest player in Serie A history to score two goals in a single league match, at the age of 39 years, 6 months and 23 days, breaking Silvio Piola's previous record of 39 years, 4 months and 2 days, which he had managed with [[Novara Calcio|Novara]] on 1 February 1953, after scoring a brace against his former team Lazio.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Serie-A/Roma/08-05-2016/roma-chievo-record-totti-600-partite-in-a-zanetti-piola-giggs-maldini-costacurta-150540661176.shtml|title=Roma-Chievo, che ovazione per le 600 in A di Totti: ora punta Zanetti a 615|trans-title=Roma-Chievo, what an ovation for Totti's 600 appearances in Serie A: now he looks to Zanetti at 615|work=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|first=Chiara|last=Zucchelli|date=8 May 2016|accessdate=9 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 May, Totti came off the bench and scored from a free kick to help Roma to come from behind and achieve a 3\u20132 away win over [[Genoa C.F.C.|Genoa]]; this was his 21st goal from a free kick in Serie A, which put him alongside Baggio as the joint all-time [[Football records in Italy#Most goals from a free kick|fourth-highest scorer of free kicks in Serie A history]], behind only [[Alessandro Del Piero]], [[Andrea Pirlo]], and [[Sini\u0161a Mihajlovi\u0107]]. Totti came off the bench in each of the past five Serie A games and contributed four goals and an assist.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.football-italia.net/83762/serie-week-36-did-you-know|title=Serie A Week 36: Did You Know?|publisher=Football Italia|first=Susy|last=Campanale|date=3 May 2016|accessdate=3 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/italian-serie-a/match/431915/genoa-as-roma/report|title=Francesco Totti helps Roma rally to victory at Genoa|publisher=ESPN FC|date=2 May 2016|accessdate=3 May 2016}}</ref> On 8 May, Totti came off the bench to set up Roma's final goal in a 3\u20130 home win over Chievo in his 600th Serie A appearance, becoming the third player ever to reach this milestone.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2016/may/08/francesco-totti-serie-a-roma-chievo|title=Francesco Totti makes 600th Serie A appearance as Roma beat Chievo 3\u20130|work=The Guardian|date=8 May 2016|accessdate=9 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thescore.com/news/1023086|title=Francesco Totti records 600th Serie A appearance|publisher=The Score|first=Carlo|last=Campo|date=8 May 2016|accessdate=9 May 2016}}</ref> Overall, Totti only made 13 league appearances throughout the season but scored four goals in the final six matches as a substitute.<ref name=\"final-contract\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/36473471|title=Francesco Totti: Roma legend signs final contract with his only club|work=BBC Sport|date=7 June 2016|accessdate=7 June 2016}}</ref> On 7 June, he renewed his contract for another year, stating that he would be retiring at the end of the [[2016\u201317 A.S. Roma season|2016\u201317 season]];<ref name=\"final-contract\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.football-italia.net/85510/confirmed-totti-renews-roma|title=Confirmed: Totti renews with Roma|publisher=Football Italia|date=7 June 2016|accessdate=7 June 2016}}</ref> he also revealed he had signed a six-year contract as Roma's technical director once the season ends.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.football-italia.net/85513/totti-%E2%80%98i%E2%80%99ll-be-technical-director%E2%80%99|title=Totti: 'I'll be technical director'|publisher=Football Italia|date=7 June 2016|accessdate=7 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn his first appearance of the [[2016\u201317 A.S. Roma season|2016\u201317 season]] against Sampdoria on 11 September, Totti equalled [[Paolo Maldini]]'s record of playing in 25 Serie A seasons. With Roma trailing 2\u20131 at half time, Totti came off the bench and assisted [[Edin D\u017eeko]]'s temporary equaliser, later also scoring the match-winning goal from a penalty in injury time to secure a 3\u20132 home win in [[2016\u201317 Serie A|Serie A]]; Totti's goal meant that he had managed to score at least once in each of the past 23 consecutive seasons of his career.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.fourfourtwo.com/news/totti-scores-last-gasp-winner-after-weather-delay|title=Totti scores last-gasp winner after weather delay|magazine=FourFourTwo|date=11 September 2016|accessdate=12 September 2016}}</ref> On 25 September, he scored his 250th Serie A goal from the penalty spot in a 3\u20131 away defeat to Torino, just two days before his 40th birthday.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.beinsports.com/au/football/video/totti-reaches-250-serie-a-goals-in-roma-defea/341769|title=Totti reaches 250 Serie A goals in Roma defeat|publisher=beIN SPORTS|date=25 September 2016|accessdate=2 October 2016}}</ref> On his first start two days after his 40th birthday, on 29 September, Totti was praised for his performance and longevity in a 4\u20130 home win over [[FC Astra Giurgiu|Astra Giurgiu]] in the [[2016\u201317 UEFA Europa League|Europa League]]; he played all 90 minutes of the match, providing two assists, while also being involved in a third goal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com/soccer/story/francesco-totti-will-never-age-grabs-two-assists-for-roma-in-europa-league-092916|title=Francesco Totti will never age, grabs two assists for Roma in Europa League|publisher=Fox Sports|first=Aaron|last=West|date=29 September 2016|accessdate=2 October 2016}}</ref> On 20 October, Totti made his 100th appearance in [[UEFA club competitions]], setting up two goals in a 3\u20133 home draw against [[FK Austria Wien|Austria Wien]] in the Europa League.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.beinsports.com/au/football/video/wily-kayode-spoils-totti-milestone/356433|title=Wily Kayode spoils Totti milestone|publisher=beIN SPORTS|date=20 October 2016|accessdate=21 October 2016}}</ref> In late October, he sustained a muscle injury to the flexor of his left thigh during a training session, which ruled him out indefinitely.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.calciomercato.com/en/news/roma-official-injured-francesco-totti-to-skip-empoli-clash-36183|title=Roma, official: injured Francesco Totti to skip Empoli clash|publisher=CalcioMercato.com|date=29 October 2016|accessdate=17 November 2016}}</ref> He returned to action as a substitute in a 3\u20132 home win over [[Delfino Pescara 1936|Pescara]] on 27 November.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://it.ibtimes.com/roma-pescara-3-2-dzeko-perotti-giallorossi-vincono-ma-fatica-video-1476361|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161201015813/http://it.ibtimes.com/roma-pescara-3-2-dzeko-perotti-giallorossi-vincono-ma-fatica-video-1476361|url-status=dead|archive-date=1 December 2016|title=Roma-Pescara 3-2: Dzeko-Perotti giallorossi vincono ma a fatica [VIDEO]|work=[[International Business Times]]|first=Marco|last=Iorio|language=Italian|date=27 November 2016|accessdate=15 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 February 2017, Totti scored a decisive injury-time penalty in the 97th minute of a 2\u20131 home victory against Cesena in the [[2016\u201317 Coppa Italia|Coppa Italia]] quarter-finals; the win enabled Roma to advance to the semi-finals of the tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.football-italia.net/97795/coppa-totti-penalty-fells-cesena|title=Coppa: Totti penalty fells Cesena|publisher=Football Italia|accessdate=2 February 2017|date=1 February 2017}}</ref> On 15 April, he came on as a substitute in a 1\u20131 home draw against Atalanta to make his 615th appearance in Serie A, equalling [[Javier Zanetti]] as the joint third highest appearance holder of all time in Serie A.<ref name=\"La Top 10 in Serie A\">{{cite web|url=http://it.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=2458711.html|title=Totti fa 615, agganciato Zanetti|publisher=UEFA.com|language=Italian|date=16 April 2017|accessdate=17 April 2017}}</ref> On 28 May, Totti made his final appearance for Roma in a 3\u20132 home win against [[Genoa C.F.C.|Genoa]], coming on as a substitute for [[Mohamed Salah]] in the 54th minute and received a standing ovation from the fans.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/40036023|title=Roma 3\u20132 Genoa|work=BBC Sport|date=28 May 2017|accessdate=28 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Francesco Totti chipped Edwin van der Sar at Euro 2000.JPG|thumbnail|right|Totti performs his chipped penalty in Italy's victorious [[UEFA Euro 2000|Euro 2000]] semi-final shootout against hosts the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]].]] -->\n\n===Youth career and early senior career===\nTotti first came into international prominence while playing in FIFA and UEFA youth tournaments. With the [[Italy national under-16 football team|Italy under-16 side]], under manager Sergio Vatta, Totti reached the final of the [[1993 UEFA European Under-16 Championship]] in Turkey; Italy were defeated 1\u20130 by [[Poland national under-16 football team|Poland]] as Totti missed the final due to suspension.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/1993/05/08/ragazzini-di-vatta-al-traguardo.html|title=I RAGAZZINI DI VATTA AL TRAGUARDO|trans-title=Vatta's boys at the finish-line|work=la Repubblica|language=Italian|date=8 May 1993|accessdate=5 May 2015}}</ref> Four months later, Totti played in [[1993 FIFA U-17 World Championship]] in Japan and scored Italy's goal in the tournament as the ''Azzurrini'' were eliminated in group stage.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/tournaments/archive/u17worldcup/japan1993/matches/round=191564/match=31280/index.html|title=FIFA U-17 World Championship Japan 1993|publisher=FIFA|language=|date=22 August 1993|accessdate=19 June 2015}}</ref> Totti also scored in [[Italy national under-19 football team|Italy's]] 4\u20131 defeat to [[Spain national under-19 football team|Spain]] in the final of the [[UEFA European Under-19 Football Championship|UEFA Under-18 Championship]], in July 1995.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/1995/luglio/23/Europei_Under_Italia_seconda_co_0_9507231784.shtml|title=Europei Under 18. l' Italia e' seconda|work=Corriere della Sera|language=Italian|date=23 July 1995|accessdate=29 January 2015}}</ref> He subsequently won the [[UEFA European Under-21 Football Championship|UEFA Under-21 Championship]] with [[Italy national under-21 football team|Italy]] in [[1996 UEFA European Under-21 Football Championship|1996]], under manager [[Cesare Maldini]]; in the final, he opened the scoring as the match ended in a 1\u20131 draw against [[Spain national under-21 football team|Spain]], although Italy were able to win the final on penalties.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/1996/giugno/01/Piccola_Italia_tre_volte_grande_co_0_96060111372.shtml|title=La Piccola Italia tre volte grande|work=Corriere della Sera|language=Italian|last1=Toti|first1=Giuseppe|date=1 June 1996|accessdate=29 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/under21/season=1996/overview/index.html|title=1996: Totti on top for Italy|publisher=www.uefa.com|date=1 June 1996|accessdate=5 October 2017}}</ref> The following year, he also played a key role in helping Italy to win a gold medal at the [[Football at the 1997 Mediterranean Games|1997 Mediterranean Games]], on home soil, scoring twice throughout the tournament.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/1997/06/26/bari-gran-finale-con-oro.html|title=BARI, GRAN FINALE CON L' ORO|work=la Repubblica|language=Italian|last1=Chiusano|first1=Mattia|date=26 June 1997|accessdate=29 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/1997/giugno/26/Ventola_profeta_patria_co_0_97062615256.shtml|title=Ventola fa il profeta in patria|work=Corriere della Sera|language=Italian|last1=Vulpio|first1=Carlo|date= 26 June 1997|accessdate=29 January 2015}}</ref> Due to his contribution in these tournaments, Totti was later included in the all-time Under-21 EURO dream team in 2015.<ref name=\"UEFA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/under21/news/newsid=2256143.html|title=Our all-time Under-21 EURO dream team|publisher=UEFA|date=17 June 2015|accessdate=19 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter starring with the ''Azzurrini'' in Italy's [[Italy national under-16 football team|under-16]], [[Italy national under-19 football team|under-19]], and under-21 sides, Totti earned his first senior cap for [[Italy national football team|Italy]] under the recently appointed international manager [[Dino Zoff]] during a 2\u20130 [[UEFA Euro 2000 qualifying|Euro 2000 qualifying]] victory against [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]] on 10 October 1998.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/2007/luglio/21/Grande_con_Zoff_Lippi_Trap_co_9_070721127.shtml|title=Grande con Zoff e Lippi Trap stravedeva per lui|work=Corriere dello Sport|language=Italian|last1=Monti|first1=Fabio|date=21 July 2007|accessdate=29 January 2015}}</ref> Totti scored his first goal for Italy on 26 April 2000 in a 2\u20130 friendly win over [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]] in Reggio Calabria.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://archiviostorico.gazzetta.it/2000/aprile/27/Finalmente_gioco_ga_0_00042713617.shtml|title=Finalmente un po' di gioco|work=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|date=27 April 2000|accessdate=29 January 2015}}</ref> He scored his first brace for Italy in a [[2006 FIFA World Cup qualification]] match in a 4\u20133 home win over [[Belarus national football team|Belarus]], on 13 October 2004.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/2004/10/14/qualificazioni-mondiali.119qualificazioni.html|title=Qualificazioni mondiali|work=la Repubblica|language=Italian|last1=Curro'|first1=Enrico|date=14 October 2004|accessdate=29 January 2015}}</ref> In total, Totti made 58 appearances for Italy between 1998 and 2006, scoring nine goals and making 24 assists.<ref name=\"gazzetta.it\">{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Nazionale/Primo_Piano/2007/07_Luglio/20/totti.shtml|title=Totti: \"Nazionale addio La priorit\u00e0 \u00e8 la Roma\"|work=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|date=20 July 2007|accessdate=29 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Nazionale in cifre: Totti, Francesco\">{{cite web|url=https://www.figc.it/it/nazionali/nazionali-in-cifre/dettaglio-convocato/?calciatoreId=43333&squadraId=12|title=Nazionale in cifre: Totti, Francesco|publisher=FIGC|language=Italian|accessdate=24 April 2015}}</ref>[[File:Totti Euro 2000.jpg|thumb|right|Totti (right) celebrates alongside teammate [[Alessandro Del Piero]] at [[Uefa Euro 2000|Euro 2000]]. Totti's performances through the tournament earned him the number 10 shirt of Italy.]]\n\n===Euro 2000===\nItaly went to [[UEFA Euro 2000|Euro 2000]] with Totti in excellent form. Overall, he scored two goals and provided an assist during the tournament.<ref>{{cite web|title=Euro 2000 Goals & Assists|url=http://soccer-europe.com/Archives/EuropeanChampionships/Euro2000/Data/Performers.html|publisher=Soccer Europe|accessdate=12 January 2015}}</ref> His first goal of the tournament came against co-host nation [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]] in the first round, as Totti headed in [[Demetrio Albertini]]'s cross from a set-piece;<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.repubblica.it/online/camp_europeo/partita2/partita2/partita2.html|title=L'Italia non si ferma Totti illumina, chiude Fiore|work=la Repubblica|language=Italian|accessdate=29 January 2015}}</ref> he was named man of the match for his performance.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.euro2000.org/en/tournament/matchcomment/0,1074,9668,00.html|title=Italy defence the deciding factor|publisher=UEFA|date=14 June 2000|accessdate=30 June 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010308171934/http://www.euro2000.org/en/tournament/matchcomment/0,1074,9668,00.html|archivedate=8 March 2001}}</ref> His second goal of the tournament came against [[Romania national football team|Romania]] in the quarter-finals, with an accurate strike following [[Stefano Fiore]]'s assist.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.raisport.rai.it/news/eventi/euro2000/200006/24/3955184b02c4f/|title=Euro 2000: Italia-Romania (2\u20130)&nbsp;\u2013 Azzurri in semifinale|publisher=Rai Sport|language=Italian|date=24 June 2000|accessdate=29 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181112223504/http://www2.raisport.rai.it/news/eventi/euro2000/200006/24/3955184b02c4f/|archive-date=12 November 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> In Italy's semi-final [[Penalty shootout|shootout]] victory over co-hosts the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]], Totti's confidently [[Panenka (penalty kick)|chipped penalty]] was named as one of the \"magic moments\" of the tournament.<ref name=\"Mo je faccio er cucchiaio\">{{cite news|url=http://www.repubblica.it/2005/j/sezioni/sport/calcio/librototti/librototti/librototti.html|title=\"Mo je faccio er cucchiaio\" Totti sta scrivendo un nuovo libro|work=la Repubblica|language=Italian|date=29 October 2005|accessdate=29 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Football%3A+10+MAGIC+MOMENTS+FROM+EURO+2000.-a063104967|title=Football: 10 MAGIC MOMENTS FROM EURO 2000.|publisher=The Free Library|date=4 July 2000|accessdate=28 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nThough Italy lost to [[1998 FIFA World Cup|reigning World Cup Champions]] [[France national football team|France]] 2\u20131 in extra time in the [[UEFA Euro 2000 Final|final]], Totti was named the man of the match, and he started the play which led to [[Marco Delvecchio]]'s opening goal; Totti sent an unmarked [[Gianluca Pessotto]] down the right wing with a back-heel pass, allowing him space to cross the ball into the area, where it was put into the net by Delvecchio.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ilsole24ore.com/art/SoleOnLine4/Sport/europei-nella-storia/europei-nella-storia-2000.shtml?uuid=9c1964f2-313d-11dd-9186-00000e251029&DocRulesView=Libero|title=2000, Italia battuta in finale. L'Europeo alla Francia|newspaper=Il Sole 24 Ore|language=Italian|accessdate=29 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=profile>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/teamsandplayers/players/player=15895/profile/index.html|title=Francesco Totti|publisher=UEFA|accessdate=31 May 2011}}</ref> Later, during the second half of the match, Totti provided two scoring opportunities for Alessandro Del Piero, which the Juventus forward was unable to convert.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://it.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=2000/matches/round=1461/match=65299/postmatch/report/index.html|title=Gol d'oro per Trezeguet e la Francia|trans-title=Golden goal for Trezeguet and France|publisher=UEFA|language=Italian|date=6 October 2003|accessdate=29 January 2015}}</ref> Totti was selected for the 22-man [[UEFA Euro 2000#UEFA Team of the Tournament|Team of the Tournament]] due to his performances throughout the European Championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rivistasportiva.com/rubriche/item/1282-la-storia-degli-europei-2000-francia-italia-e-il-golden-gol|title=Storia degli Europei: 2000, Francia Italia e il golden gol|publisher=Rivista Sportiva|language=Italian|accessdate=29 January 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141031211437/http://rivistasportiva.com/rubriche/item/1282-la-storia-degli-europei-2000-francia-italia-e-il-golden-gol|archivedate=31 October 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===2002 World Cup===\nAfter being handed the [[Squad number (association football)|number 10 shirt]] and Italy's [[Playmaker|playmaking]] duties, much was expected of Totti in his debut [[FIFA World Cup|World Cup]] under manager [[Giovanni Trapattoni]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Totti: \"Quell'arbitro era in malafede\"|url=http://www.repubblica.it/online/mondiali2002/totticorea/totticorea/totticorea.html|work=la Repubblica|date=18 June 2002|accessdate=29 January 2015}}</ref> Despite a promising start at the [[2002 FIFA World Cup|2002 World Cup]] held in Japan and Korea, as he set-up [[Christian Vieri]]'s first goal in Italy's 2\u20130 opening win over [[Ecuador national football team|Ecuador]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.repubblica.it/online/mondiali2002/itaecu/itaecu/itaecu.html|title=L'Italia parte bene Battuto l'Ecuador 2\u20130|work=la Repubblica|first=Massimo|last=Vincenzi|language=Italian|date=3 June 2002|accessdate=29 January 2015}}</ref> disappointment followed, with Totti failing to score or make a significant impact throughout the tournament. Despite helping to set up Vieri's goal in a disappointing and controversial 2\u20131 defeat to [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]] in Italy's second group match,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.repubblica.it/online/mondiali2002/filmcroazia/filmcroazia/filmcroazia.html|title=Il film: la cronaca di Italia-Croazia|work=la Repubblica|language=Italian|first=Dario|last=Olivero|date=8 June 2002|accessdate=29 January 2015}}</ref> his lacklustre performances throughout the tournament were later criticised by the Italian media, in particular his failure to capitalise on several scoring chances in Italy's 1\u20131 draw against [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]] in their final group match, as Italy only narrowly qualified for the knockout stage.<ref>{{cite news|title=Totti, orgoglio di campione \"Mi rifar\u00f2 contro la Corea\"|url=http://www.repubblica.it/online/mondiali2002/francesco/francesco/francesco.html|work=la Repubblica|first=Massimo|last=Vincenzi|date=16 June 2002|accessdate=29 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Del Piero e l' Ecuador tengono a galla l' Italia|url=http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/2002/giugno/14/Del_Piero_Ecuador_tengono_galla_co_0_02061410306.shtml|publisher=Il Corriere della Sera|language=Italian|date=14 June 2002|accessdate=29 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nDespite setting up Vieri's goal in Italy's [[2002 FIFA World Cup knockout stage#South Korea vs Italy|second round defeat to co-hosts]] [[South Korea national football team|South Korea]] from a corner,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.repubblica.it/diretta/online/coreita/|title=Corea del Sud-Italia 2\u20131|work=la Repubblica|language=Italian|last1=Tonelli|first1=Matteo|date=18 June 2002|accessdate=29 January 2015}}</ref> his performance was once again criticised,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Costa|first1=Alberto|title=Totti in fuga dalle barzellette \"Voglio un anno da scudetto\"|url=http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/2002/settembre/12/Totti_fuga_dalle_barzellette_Voglio_co_0_0209129866.shtml|work=Corriere della Sera|accessdate=29 January 2015}}</ref> in particular as he was [[Misconduct (football)|sent off]] in extra time after being handed a controversial second yellow card by referee [[Byron Moreno]] for [[Diving (association football)|simulation]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/2002/06/19/la-gara-choc.html|title=LA GARA CHOC|work=la Repubblica|language=Italian|last1=Curro|first1=Enrico|date=19 June 2002|accessdate=29 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Euro 2004===\nAlthough he was once again expected to be Italy's star player in the number 10 role, Totti acquired a measure of infamy at [[UEFA Euro 2004|Euro 2004]] after he spat at [[Denmark national football team|Danish]] midfielder [[Christian Poulsen]] in a goalless draw in Italy's opening group match of the tournament on 14 June 2004. He was subsequently banned until the semi-finals,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.repubblica.it/diretta/online/sport-calcio-tottiday/index.html|title=Il giorno di Totti|work=la Repubblica|language=Italian|accessdate=29 January 2015}}</ref> but never made it back to action and finished the competition scoreless due to Italy's elimination in the first round on direct encounters, following a three-way five point tie with [[Sweden national football team|Sweden]] and Denmark.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.storiedicalcio.altervista.org/europei_2004.html|title=La Storia dei Campionati Europei di Calcio&nbsp;\u2013 2004: GRECIA|publisher=Storie di Calcio|language=Italian|accessdate=29 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n===2006 World Cup===\n[[File:MostraImmagineFoto 5.aspx.jpg|thumb|right|Totti (right), [[President of Italy]] [[Giorgio Napolitano]] and the team celebrate victory in the [[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006 World Cup]]]]\n\nDespite injury troubles, Totti recovered in time to join the national team for their victorious [[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006 World Cup]] campaign, despite a lack of match practice during his three months on the sidelines. Italy manager [[Marcello Lippi]] showed enormous faith in Totti, assuring him during his rehabilitation that his spot in Italy's World Cup squad was secure and to focus on recuperating. This encouragement and show of faith fueled Totti's desire to work even harder to overcome what could have been a career-ending injury and make it to the World Cup against all odds (and much of the Italian media's opinion).<ref>{{cite news|title=Aspettando Godot, anche al Mondiale|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Speciali/Mondiale_2006/Primo_Piano/2006/06_Giugno/22/godot.html|work=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|date=22 June 2006|accessdate=29 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Top of the World\">{{cite web|url=http://www.football-italia.net/Francesco-Totti/Totti-Italy-World-Cup-2006|title=Top of the World|publisher=Football Italia|author1=Giancarlo Rinaldi|accessdate=17 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nTotti did recuperate in time and was eventually named to Lippi's final 23-man squad for the 2006 World Cup.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.repubblica.it/2006/05/sezioni/sport/calcio/nazionale/conferenza-stampa-lippi/conferenza-stampa-lippi/conferenza-stampa-lippi.html|title=Lippi ha fiducia, nonostante tutto Convocato Buffon: \"E' sereno\"|newspaper=La Repubblica|language=Italian|date=15 May 2006|accessdate=20 January 2017}}</ref> Despite initial concerns over his match fitness, Totti was an important player in Marcello Lippi's team,<ref name=\"Top of the World\"/><ref name=\"tattered international reputation\"/><ref name=\"Cesare Prandelli can't afford to leave Totti\"/> and played in all seven games for Italy,<ref name=blitzquotidiano>{{cite web|url=http://www.blitzquotidiano.it/sport/italia-2006-campioni-del-mondo-grosso-jolly-cannavaro-buffon-voto-simpatia-75-1883864/|title=Home Sport Italia 2006: campioni del mondo. Grosso jolly, Cannavaro e Buffon muro: voto simpatia 7,5|publisher=BlitzQuotidiano.it|language=Italian|first=Antonio|last=Sansonetti|date=6 June 2014|accessdate=3 July 2016}}</ref> including the victorious [[2006 FIFA World Cup Final|final]] against France, which Italy won on penalties, although he was substituted off in the 61st minute.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/world_cup_2006/4991652.stm|title=Italy 1\u20131 France (aet)|work=BBC Sport|last=Stevenson|first=Jonathan|date=9 July 2006|accessdate=28 June 2012}}</ref> He played the entire time in Germany with metal plates and screws in his ankle that had yet to be removed following the surgery.<ref name=\"Top of the World\"/><ref name=\"tattered international reputation\"/><ref name=\"Cesare Prandelli can't afford to leave Totti\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/why-cesare-prandelli-cant-afford-leave-totti-behind-brazil-summer|title=Why Cesare Prandelli can't afford to leave Totti behind for Brazil this summer|magazine=FourFourTwo|author1=Richard Whittle|date=14 April 2014|accessdate=17 July 2017}}</ref> Throughout the tournament, he usually played as an attacking midfielder, in front of deep-lying playmaker Andrea Pirlo, and behind strikers [[Luca Toni]], [[Alberto Gilardino]], [[Vincenzo Iaquinta]], or [[Filippo Inzaghi]]; these players were supported defensively by [[Gennaro Gattuso]], [[Simone Perrotta]] and Daniele De Rossi in midfield.<ref name=blitzquotidiano/> Totti finished the tournament with the joint-highest number of assists, along with his teammate Pirlo, [[Juan Rom\u00e1n Riquelme]], [[Bastian Schweinsteiger]], and [[Lu\u00eds Figo]] (4).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/28123120|title=World Cup 2014: Today at the tournament&nbsp;\u2013 day 23|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=29 January 2015}}</ref> Totti set up Pirlo's goal from a short corner in Italy's opening 2\u20130 win against [[Ghana national football team|Ghana]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/world_cup_2006/4852746.stm |title=BBC SPORT &#124; Football &#124; World Cup 2006 &#124; Italy 2\u20130 Ghana |work=BBC News |date= 12 June 2006|accessdate=28 June 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.calcioblog.it/post/784/mondiali-2006-italia-2-ghana-0|title=Mondiali 2006: Italia 2 Ghana 0|accessdate=29 January 2015}}</ref> [[Marco Materazzi]]'s goal from a corner in Italy's final group match, a 2\u20130 win against the [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech Republic]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.repubblica.it/speciale/2006/mondiali/dati/dirette/1596550.html|title=Rep. Ceca-Italia 0\u20132|work=la Repubblica|language=Italian|date=22 June 2006|accessdate=29 January 2015}}</ref> and two goals in a 3\u20130 win against [[Ukraine national football team|Ukraine]] in the quarter-finals: the opener by [[Gianluca Zambrotta]], and one of Luca Toni's goals.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.repubblica.it/2006/06/speciale/altri/2006mondialipartite/ucraina-italia/ucraina-italia.html|title=La difesa era perfetta, ora anche l'attacco Doppietta Toni, Ucraina sconfitta|work=la Repubblica|language=Italian|date=30 June 2006|accessdate=29 January 2015}}</ref> Totti also scored a goal via an injury-time penalty in Italy's 1\u20130 round of 16 win over [[Australia national soccer team|Australia]] on 26 June,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.repubblica.it/2006/06/speciale/altri/2006mondialipartite/italia-australia/italia-australia.html|newspaper=La Repubblica|title=Mondiali, l'Italia nei quarti Totti su rigore: vittoria al 95'|language=Italian|date=26 June 2006|accessdate=29 January 2015}}</ref> and was involved in Del Piero's last-minute extra-time goal in the semi-final, which sealed a 2\u20130 victory for the Italians over hosts [[Germany national football team|Germany]], and a place in the World Cup final.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/07/05/sports/05iht-wcitaly.2120840.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0|title=Italy 2, Germany 0: Jinx holds as Italians reach final&nbsp;\u2013 Sports&nbsp;\u2013 International Herald Tribune|work=The New York Times|first=Roger|last=Cohen|date=5 July 2006|accessdate=27 July 2016}}</ref> Throughout the competition, Totti completed 185 passes and took 19 shots;<ref name=blitzquotidiano/> in recognition of a successful tournament, he was selected for the 23-man [[2006 FIFA World Cup#All star team|All-Star Team]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/germany2006/news/newsid=31923.html#iazzurrii+prominent+all+star+team|title=Azzurri prominent in All Star Team|publisher=FIFA.com|date=7 July 2006|accessdate=31 May 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100614214225/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/germany2006/news/newsid%3D31923.html#iazzurrii+prominent+all+star+team|archivedate=14 June 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Retirement===\nTotti intended to retire from international football after the 2006 World Cup, but reneged on his decision and remained undecided on his future for over a year, not being called up in the meantime. He made his retirement official on 20 July 2007, at the beginning of the [[2007\u201308 Serie A]] season, due to recurring physical problems<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=http://www.corriere.it/Primo_Piano/Sport/2007/07_Luglio/20/totti_lascia_nazionale.shtml|title=Totti dice addio alla Nazionale|work=Corriere della Sera|language=Italian|date=20 July 2007|accessdate=29 January 2015}}</ref> and in order to focus solely on club play with Roma.<ref name=\"gazzetta.it\"/> Italy's coach at the time, [[Roberto Donadoni]], attempted to get Totti to change his mind for the remaining [[UEFA Euro 2008|Euro 2008]] qualifiers but was not successful.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/6908413.stm|title=Totti ends international career|work=BBC Sport|date=20 July 2007|accessdate=1 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nAfter Marcello Lippi's reappointment as the national team's manager following Euro 2008, Totti announced that he would play in the [[2010 FIFA World Cup|2010 World Cup]] finals in South Africa if he were to receive a call-up;<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/SerieA/Roma/02-01-2010/totti-apertura-mondiale-602515730259.shtml|title=Totti, apertura Mondiale \"Se Lippi chiama dico s\u00ec\"|work=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|date=2 January 2010|accessdate=29 January 2015}}</ref> however, there was no official statement release from Totti or Lippi about a possible comeback.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/oct/13/francesco-totti-return-italy|title=Francesco Totti considers Italy comeback|work=The Guardian|date=13 October 2009|accessdate=13 July 2014}}</ref> For the final tournament, Totti was not named in the 23-man squad, and Italy was subsequently eliminated, failing to win a match and finishing last in their group, their worst-ever World Cup performance. [[Diego Maradona]] and former national teammates [[Fabio Cannavaro]] and [[Gianluigi Buffon]] said one of the reasons for Italy's early exit was due to the lack of creative players like Totti in the team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.forzaroma.info/2010/06/26/maradonaqlitalia-eliminata-mi-dispiace-ma-ci-voleva-uno-come-tottiq-21779/27549|title=Maradona:\"L'Italia eliminata? Mi dispiace, ma ci voleva uno come Totti&nbsp;...\"|publisher=Forzaroma.info|language=Italian|date=26 June 2010|accessdate=13 July 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714192852/http://www.forzaroma.info/2010/06/26/maradonaqlitalia-eliminata-mi-dispiace-ma-ci-voleva-uno-come-tottiq-21779/27549|archivedate=14 July 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2013, Lippi's successor as Italy's coach, [[Cesare Prandelli]], stated that he would consider Totti for the [[2014 FIFA World Cup|2014 World Cup]] squad.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Mondiali/26-03-2014/mondiale-prandelli-balotelli-ascolta-seedorf-tira-fuori-tue-emozioni-80316055172.shtml|title=Mondiale, Prandelli: \"Cassano e Totti? Porte aperte in Nazionale\"|work=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|date=26 March 2014|accessdate=29 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://gazzettadireggio.gelocal.it/sport/2013/10/08/news/prandelli-oggi-porterei-totti-ai-mondiali-1.7890792|title=Prandelli: \"Oggi porterei Totti ai Mondiali\"|work=La Gazzetta di Reggio|language=Italian|date=8 October 2013|accessdate=29 January 2015}}</ref> In October 2013, Prandelli said, \"Totti is in fantastic form. His condition right now does make you reflect. If the World Cup was around the corner, I would have no doubts and would absolutely call him up. But we will evaluate the player's condition one month prior to the World Cup.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theworldgame.sbs.com.au/world-cup/news/1169635/Totti-still-in-Prandelli-s-thoughts?|title=Totti still in Prandelli's thoughts|work=SBS|date=8 October 2013}}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> However, at the time of the choice of the final 23-man Italian squad for the World Cup, the Italy coach excluded the Roma striker, preferring to focus the team around younger players.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Nazionale/15-05-2014/prandelli-intervista-esclusiva-forum-totti-rossi-cassano-balotelli-berlusconi-immobile-80680254974.shtml|title=Prandelli: \"Italia da finale. Totti? Ci avevo pensato, Immobile come Pablito\"|work=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|first1=Andrea|last1=Elefante|first2=Sebastiano|last2=Vernazza|date=16 May 2014|accessdate=29 January 2015}}</ref> Some in the media criticised the decision, such as former Brazilian international footballer [[Cafu]], who had been Totti's teammate at Roma, who revealed that he would have liked to see Totti competing for Italy at the World Cup in Brazil, and that he preferred the Roma captain over [[Cristiano Ronaldo]] and [[Lionel Messi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://forzaitalianfootball.com/2014/06/cafu-messi-or-ronaldo-i-say-totti/|title=Cafu: Messi Or Ronaldo? I Say Totti|publisher=Forza Italian Football|date=20 June 2014|accessdate=13 July 2014}}</ref> Without Totti, Italy was eliminated in the first round for the second consecutive time, finishing third in their group.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://globalnews.ca/news/1413275/world-cup-italy-bounced-from-world-cup-in-1-0-loss-to-uruguay/|title=WORLD CUP: Italy bounced from World Cup in 1\u20130 loss to Uruguay|publisher=Global News|date=24 June 2014|accessdate=13 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.corrieredellosport.it/foto/calcio/mondiali_2014/girone-d/italia/2014/06/24-91707_3/Italia+fuori+dal+Mondiale%3A+il+web+rimpiange+Totti|title=Italia fuori dal Mondiale: il web rimpiange Totti|work=Corriere dello Sport|language=Italian|date=24 June 2014|accessdate=13 July 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714174652/http://www.corrieredellosport.it/foto/calcio/mondiali_2014/girone-d/italia/2014/06/24-91707_3/Italia+fuori+dal+Mondiale%3A+il+web+rimpiange+Totti|archivedate=14 July 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2016, several injuries in the Italian squad, as well as a lack of attacking options and Totti's run of good form as a substitute for Roma, led some in the media to call for manager [[Antonio Conte]] to include Totti as a reserve in Italy's [[UEFA Euro 2016|Euro 2016]] squad; however, he was later left out of Conte's 30-man preliminary Italy squad for the final tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.calciomercato.com/en/news/should-totti-go-to-euro-2016-vote-now-653726|title=Should Totti go to Euro 2016? VOTE NOW!|publisher=Calciomercato.com|date=3 May 2016|accessdate=9 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2016/05/30/italy-euro-2016-squad/|title=Italy Euro 2016 squad|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=1 June 2016|accessdate=1 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Style of play==\n{{Quote box|width=28%|align=right|quote=\"A great player! What a phenomenon!\"|source=\u2014 [[Lionel Messi]] comments on Totti after the 50th anniversary of the [[Joan Gamper Trophy|Joan Gamper trophy]], between [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] and Roma.<ref>{{cite news|title=Messi to Totti: \"What a phenomenon\"|url=http://www.weloba.com/messi-to-totti-what-a-phenomenon|date=6 August 2015|accessdate=8 September 2015|publisher=weloba.com|language=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180909035754/http://www.weloba.com/messi-to-totti-what-a-phenomenon|archive-date=9 September 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Messi, omaggio a Totti su Instagram: \"Un grande, che fenomeno\"|url=http://www.repubblica.it/sport/2015/08/06/foto/messi_foto_con_totti_un_grande_che_fenomeno_-120509283/1/#1|date=6 August 2015|accessdate=8 September 2015|work=la Repubblica|language=Italian}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Messi sobre Totti: \"\u00a1Qu\u00e9 fen\u00f3meno!\"|url=http://www.directvsports.net/noticias/article/uuid/11yqm3wxi0q9o1dyv8a0cy6qvz/messi-sobre-totti-que-fenomeno|date=6 August 2015|accessdate=8 September 2015|publisher=DIRECTV sports|language=Spanish}}</ref>}}\n{{Quote box|width=28%|align=right|quote=\"Totti is an artist of football, a true [[Squad number (association football)|Number 10]].\"|source=\u2014 [[Michel Platini]], former French midfielder and former [[UEFA]] President.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tuttomercatoweb.com/rassegna-stampa/platini-totti-artista-del-calcio-46179|title=Platini: \"Totti artista del calcio\"|publisher=TuttoMercatoWeb|language=Italian|date=27 December 2006|accessdate=24 April 2014}}</ref>}}\n{{Quote box|width=28%|align=right|quote=\"Totti is immortal and he is a symbol of our sport. I only regret not having worked with him.\"|source=\u2014 [[Carlo Ancelotti]], former Italian midfielder and three time Champions League winning football manager.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.asromachannel.eu/notizie-as-roma/as-roma-2/ancelotti-su-totti-e-immortale-e-il-simbolo-di-questo-sport-dispiace-non-averlo-allenato-ma-mai-dire-mai-18974|title=ANCELOTTI SU TOTTI: \"E' IMMORTALE E IL SIMBOLO DI QUESTO SPORT. DISPIACE NON AVERLO ALLENATO, MA MAI DIRE MAI\"|publisher=As Roma Channel|language=Italian|date=29 December 2014|accessdate=8 September 2015}}</ref>}}\n\n[[File:Totti back 2011.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Totti wore [[playmaker|number 10]] for most of his club career]]Often referred to as ''Er Bimbo de Oro'' (The Golden Boy), ''L'Ottavo Re di Roma'' (The Eighth King of Rome), ''Er Pupone'' (The Big Baby), ''Il Capitano''  (The Captain), and ''Il Gladiatore'' (The Gladiator) by the Italian sports media,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.football-italia.net/Francesco-Totti/Totti-the-Roman-Icon|title=Totti, the Last Gladiator|author1=Andrea Tallarita|publisher=Football Italia|accessdate=18 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://roma.corriere.it/foto-gallery/cronaca/17_aprile_26/totti-come-l-ottavo-re-roma-3166a184-2aa7-11e7-aac7-9deed828925b.shtml|title=Totti come \"l\u2019ottavo re di Roma\"|publisher=Il Corriere della Sera|language=Italian|accessdate=18 June 2017}}</ref> Totti is considered to be one of the greatest Italian players of all time,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theworldgame.sbs.com.au/article/2014/02/14/mihajlovic-totti-best-ever-italian|title=Mihajlovic: Totti is best ever Italian|date=14 May 2014|publisher=[[The World Game]]|accessdate=6 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://forzaitalianfootball.com/2013/10/ranking-francesco-totti-in-italian-football-doesnt-make-sense/|title=Where Does Francesco Totti Stand In The Pantheon Of Italian Football?|date=October 2013|accessdate=6 September 2015|publisher=Forza Italian Football}}</ref><ref name=\"Roma, \u00e8 Totti il miglior calciatore italiano di sempre?\">{{cite web|url=http://video.sky.it/sport/calcio-italiano/totti_il_miglior_italiano_di_sempre_roma/v173907.vid|title=Roma, \u00e8 Totti il miglior calciatore italiano di sempre?|date=9 October 2013|publisher=Sky Italia|language=Italian|accessdate=15 June 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Roma, Totti nella storia. Genoa ko, -5 dal Milan\">{{cite news|url=http://www.corrieredellosport.it/serie_a/roma/2013/03/03-307973/Roma,+Totti+nella+storia.+Genoa+ko,+-5+dal+Milan|title=Roma, Totti nella storia. Genoa ko, \u22125 dal Milan|last=Cotugno|first=Vladimiro|date=3 March 2013|work=Corriere dello Sport|accessdate=15 June 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924050812/http://www.corrieredellosport.it/serie_a/roma/2013/03/03-307973/Roma,+Totti+nella+storia.+Genoa+ko,+-5+dal+Milan|archivedate=24 September 2015|language=Italian|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Rivera vota Totti\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Squadre/Roma/17-02-2013/rivera-totti-piu-un-numero-10-baggio-piero-mancini-scelgo-lui-9256802452.shtml|title=Rivera vota Totti: \"Meglio di Baggio e Del Piero. E' il pi\u00f9 grande degli ultimi 30 anni\"|date=18 February 2013|work=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|accessdate=15 June 2015}}</ref> one of the best players of his generation,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Squadre/Roma/08-09-2013/roma-garcia-totti-dei-migliori-storia-calcio-201120629784.shtml|title=Roma, Garcia: \"Totti uno dei migliori nella storia del calcio\"|last=Calabresi|first=Marco|date=8 September 2013|work=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|accessdate=15 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/sep/27/francesco-totti-eternal-quality-roma-manchester-city-champions-league|title=Francesco Totti still providing eternal quality for his beloved Roma|accessdate=4 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Totti:Goal, musica, emozioni\">{{cite news|url=http://www.corrieredellosport.it/articoli/articolo_585.shtml|title=Totti:Goal, musica, emozioni&nbsp;...|date=29 November 2008|work=Corriere dello Sport|accessdate=22 April 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222162302/http://www.corrieredellosport.it/articoli/articolo_585.shtml|archivedate=22 February 2014|language=Italian|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and Roma's greatest ever player.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.football-italia.net/150issue/tottiicon.html|title=Calcio Italia Icons: Francesco Totti|date=February 2008|accessdate=31 May 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111018182910/http://football-italia.net/150issue/tottiicon.html|archivedate=18 October 2011|publisher=Football Italia|language=|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Totti is also regarded by some as Italy's greatest player ever.<ref name=\"Roma, \u00e8 Totti il miglior calciatore italiano di sempre?\" /><ref name=\"Roma, Totti nella storia. Genoa ko, -5 dal Milan\" /><ref name=\"Rivera vota Totti\" /> Throughout his career, he played predominantly as a classic number 10, functioning either as an [[Midfielder#Attacking midfielder|offensive-midfield]] [[Playmaker#Advanced playmakers|playmaker]] or as a supporting or [[Forward (association football)#Second striker|deep-lying forward]] behind the main striker;<ref name=\"Francesco Totti (attaccante e trequartista)\">{{cite web|url=http://www.asroma-calcio.com/roma-squadra-calcio/totti.html|title=Francesco Totti (attaccante e trequartista)|publisher=A.S. Roma Calcio|language=Italian|accessdate=15 June 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061016100055/http://www.asroma-calcio.com/Roma-squadra-calcio/totti.html|archivedate=16 October 2006}}</ref><ref name=\"chameleon\">{{cite web|url=http://www.football-italia.net/Francesco-Totti/The-Tactical-Chameleon-part-1|title=Totti the tactical chameleon|publisher=Football Italia|author1=Gaby McKay|accessdate=11 April 2017}}</ref> only in the later years of his Roma career was he mainly employed as a lone [[Forward (association football)#Striker|striker]].<ref name=\"Attacchi d'Europa Scontro tra titani\">{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Primo_Piano/2007/06_Giugno/24/attacchi.html|title=Attacchi d'Europa Scontro tra titani|work=La Gazzetta dello Sport|first=Riccardo|last=Pratesi|language=Italian|date=24 June 2007|accessdate=15 June 2015}}</ref> An elegant, world-class, and technically gifted attacking midfielder with a good knowledge of the game, Totti was a tactically versatile player, capable of playing anywhere along the front line, and was also occasionally deployed as a [[Forward (association football)#Winger|winger]] or as a [[Midfielder#Central midfielder|central midfielder]] under Zden\u011bk Zeman,<ref name=\"Why Stop Now?\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/04/17/sports/soccer/20-creative-years-of-francesco-totti-why-stop.html?_r=0|title=After 2 Decades of Creativity: Why Stop Now?|work=The New York Times|first=Rob|last=Hughes|date=16 April 2013|accessdate=20 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/it/news/2/serie-a/2012/06/04/3147225/returnfalse|title=Lamela come Totti: con Zeman si torna al 1997, quando Totti ricamava all'ala. 'Coco' pu\u00f2 diventare nuovo idolo della sinistra|publisher=Goal.com|language=Italian|date=4 June 2012|accessdate=15 June 2015}}</ref> and most notably as a [[Forward (association football)#False 9|false-9]] under Luciano Spalletti and Rudi Garcia.<ref name=\"great team tactics\" /><ref name=\"Attacchi d'Europa Scontro tra titani\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/blog/2009/oct/27/the-question-false-nines-jonathan-wilson|title=The Question: Why are teams so tentative about false nines?|work=The Guardian|first=Jonathan|last=Wilson|date=27 October 2009|accessdate=15 June 2015}}</ref> Under Luis Enrique, he was also occasionally fielded in a more withdrawn creative role in midfield, functioning as a [[Midfielder#Deep-lying playmaker|deep-lying playmaker]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.calciomercato.com/news/la-roma-a-bologna-due-rossi-e-totti-registi-877298|title=La Roma \u00e8 cambiata: De Rossi e Totti registi|trans-title=Roma has changed: De Rossi and Totti deep-lying playmakers|publisher=Calciomercato|language=Italian|first=Valerio|last=Nasetti|date=22 December 2012|accessdate=18 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nWhile Totti was a prolific goalscorer, he was also renowned for his ball control, vision, creativity, and range of passing, as well as his ability to set the pace in midfield and provide through-balls and [[Assist (football)|assists]] for his teammates, often through his trademark use of the no-look pass or [[backheel]], in particular when holding up the ball or playing with his back to goal. Throughout his career, Totti drew particular praise from pundits for his excellent vision, technique, and precise long passing ability, which allowed him to play the ball first-time.<ref name=\"Roma, Totti punta ai mille tacchi\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sportmediaset.mediaset.it/calcio/roma/articoli/89072/roma-totti-punta-ai-mille-tacchi.shtml|title=Roma, Totti punta ai \"mille tacchi\"|publisher=Sport Mediaset|language=Italian|date=8 September 2012|accessdate=15 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/premium/plus/Calcio/Squadre/Roma/08-09-2012/totti-insegue-tacco-n-1000-912544472134.shtml|title=Totti, altro traguardo Insegue il tacco n\u00b0 1000|work=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|first=Andrea|last=Pugliese|date=8 September 2012|accessdate=16 February 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"=Del Piero, Totti e Baggio la fantasia al potere\">{{cite news|url=http://www.repubblica.it/online/calcio/fantasisti/fantasisti/fantasisti.html|title=Del Piero, Totti e Baggio la fantasia al potere|work=la Repubblica|language=Italian|first=Andrea|last=Di Nicola|date=6 October 2001|accessdate=16 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.corrieredellosport.it/news/calcio/serie-a/roma/2015/11/11-5783810/la_roma_e_il_rientro_di_totti/?cookieAccept|title=La Roma e il rientro di Totti|work=Corriere dello Sport|language=Italian|date=11 November 2015|accessdate=16 February 2016}}</ref> Due to his movement and range of skills, his role has at times been described as that of a hardworking, unselfish and dynamic [[Forward (association football)#Centre-forward|centre]] [[Forward (association football)|forward]], known as a ''centravanti di manovra'' in Italian (which literally translates to \"manoeuvring centre-forward\").<ref name=\"Goals\" /><ref name=\"Attacchi d'Europa Scontro tra titani\" /> Known for his work rate, longevity, and willingness to contribute defensively, Totti underwent an athletic development during his time under Zeman: he undertook a muscle-strengthening programme to adapt to the rhythms of 21st-century football, gaining physical strength, stamina, fitness and shooting power to the detriment of some of his speed and agility, which also enabled him to maintain a consistent level of performance in his later career.<ref name=\"Rome's greatest son\" /><ref name=\"Totti, pi\u00f9 muscoli al servizio della fantasia\">{{cite news|url=http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/1998/novembre/07/Totti_piu_muscoli_servizio_della_co_0_9811078539.shtml|title=Totti, piu' muscoli al servizio della fantasia|work=Corriere della Sera|first=Giorgio|last=Rondelli|language=Italian|date=7 November 1998|accessdate=22 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2000/jun/24/euro2000.sport8|title=Del Piero fuels passionate debate|work=The Guardian|first=Paddy|last=Agnew|date=24 June 2000|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref>\n[[File:Francesco Totti Chelsea vs AS-Roma 10AUG2013.jpg|thumb|Totti during a pre-season friendly in 2013]]\nThroughout his career, Totti utilised his balance, [[Dribbling#Association football|dribbling skills]], and acceleration in order to get past opponents; despite being naturally right-footed, he possessed a powerful and accurate shot from both inside and outside the area with either foot,<ref name=\"Rivera vota Totti\" /><ref name=\"Francesco Totti (attaccante e trequartista)\" /><ref name=\"Roma, Totti punta ai mille tacchi\" /><ref name=\"=Del Piero, Totti e Baggio la fantasia al potere\" /> and was also an accurate [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty kick]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.repubblica.it/sport/calcio/serie-a/roma/2011/07/17/news/totti_segna_primo_gol-19251032/?refresh_ce|title=Totti lascia subito il segno \"Ancora tanto da lavorare\"|work=la Repubblica|language=Italian|date=17 July 2011|accessdate=15 June 2015}}</ref> and [[Direct free kick|free kick]] taker,<ref name=\"Totti:Goal, musica, emozioni\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asromachannel.eu/notizie-as-roma/serie-a-totti-al-sesto-posto-nella-classifica-dei-re-dei-calci-di-punizione-dal-2005-ad-oggi-39198|title=Serie A, Totti al sesto posto nella classifica dei re dei calci di punizione dal 2005 ad oggi|publisher=A.S. Roma Channel|language=Italian|date=11 May 2015|accessdate=15 June 2015}}</ref> who was capable of striking the ball either with power or [[Curl (football)|swerve]] from set pieces.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://archiviostorico.gazzetta.it//2004/marzo/13/Professione_cecchino_sw_0_040313908.shtml |title=Professione cecchino |newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport |language=Italian |author1=Fabrizio Salvio |date=13 March 2004 |accessdate=11 February 2019 }}</ref> Totti also scored several goals from [[Chip (association football)|chipped]] [[Shooting (association football)|shots]] throughout his career, and often used the [[Panenka (penalty kick)|technique on penalties]], which was also known as the ''cucchiaio'' technique (or \"spoon\" in Italian);<ref name=\"Auguri Panenka, l'inventore del cucchiaio\">{{cite news|url=http://sport.ilmessaggero.it/calcio/news/panenka-inventore-cucchiaio-totti-voeller-zidane/1042245.shtml|title=Auguri Panenka, l'inventore del \"cucchiaio\": da Voeller a Zidane e Totti, ecco i suoi eredi|work=[[Il Messaggero]]|language=Italian|first=Benedetto|last=Sacc\u00e0|date=1 December 2014|accessdate=15 June 2015}}</ref><ref>In [[Italy|Italian]] [[Association football|football]] jargon, ''fare il cucchiaio'' ({{lang-en|do the \"spoon\"}}, ''take a \"spoon\" shot'') is a colloquial expression used when taking a chip shot or a [[Panenka (penalty kick)|Panenka penalty]].</ref> one of the most famous instances in which Totti performed this type of penalty was in the victorious shootout of Italy's Euro 2000 semi-final match against the Netherlands.<ref name=\"Auguri Panenka, l'inventore del cucchiaio\" /> One of his most famous lobbed goals, in which he dribbled past Inter's Marco Materazzi before chipping the ball over goalkeeper [[J\u00falio C\u00e9sar (football goalkeeper, born 1979)|J\u00falio C\u00e9sar]], was later named the best goal in Serie A of the [[2005\u201306 Serie A|2005\u201306 season]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://video.repubblica.it/sport/totti-i-cinque-gol-indimenticabili-il-pallonetto-contro-l-inter/121245/119730|work=la Repubblica|title=Totti, i cinque gol indimenticabili: il pallonetto contro l'Inter|first=Pier Luigi|last=Pisa|language=Italian|date=4 March 2013|accessdate=15 June 2015}}</ref> He scored another notable goal using this technique against Lazio in the 2002 ''Derby della Capitale'', which ended in a 5\u20131 win for Roma.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://video.repubblica.it/sport/totti-la-rete-nel-derby-del-2002/121249?video|title=Totti, la rete nel derby del 2002|work=la Repubblica|first=Pier Luigi|last=Pisa|language=Italian|date=4 March 2013|accessdate=15 June 2015}}</ref> The title of Totti's 2006 autobiography ''Tutto Totti'': ''Mo je faccio er cucchiaio'' ({{lang-en|All about Totti}}: ''I'm gonna chip him now'') referenced this technique, as well as the statement made to his Italy teammates before his memorable Euro 2000 semi-final shootout penalty against the Netherlands.<ref name=\"Mo je faccio er cucchiaio\" /><ref name=\"Auguri Panenka, l'inventore del cucchiaio\" /><ref>''Mo je faccio er cucchiaio'' ({{lang-it|adesso gli faccio il cucchiaio}}) is actually [[Romanesco dialect|Romanesco]], the Roman-Italian dialect Totti regularly speaks.</ref> Having served as Roma's captain for several years, Totti was praised for his leadership.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.football-italia.net/44948/totti-leadership|title=Totti on leadership|publisher=Football Italia|date=7 February 2014|accessdate=2 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nDespite his talent and ability, however, Totti drew criticism at times for his character and lack of discipline on the pitch, which occasionally caused him to commit bad fouls and receive unnecessary bookings; with [[Football records in Italy#Bookings|eleven red cards, he has the joint-sixth highest number of sending offs in Serie A history]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20101101/football/ranieri-defends-irate-totti-after-red-card.334125|title=Ranieri defends irate Totti after red card|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=1 November 2010|accessdate=2 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://romanews.eu/it,a112023/Totti-11-Espulsioni-Nessuno-Rosso-Come-Lui-Giocatori-In-Attivita-Serie-Br,m82|title=Totti, 11 espulsioni. Nessuno \u2018rosso' come lui tra i giocatori in attivit\u00e0 della Serie A|publisher=RomaNews.eu|language=Italian|accessdate=11 September 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808122414/http://romanews.eu/it,a112023/Totti-11-Espulsioni-Nessuno-Rosso-Come-Lui-Giocatori-In-Attivita-Serie-Br,m82|archivedate=8 August 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.contra-ataque.it/2016/02/16/calciatori-espulsi-serie-a-montero.html|title=I calciatori pi\u00f9 espulsi nella storia della Serie A: Montero irraggiungibile|publisher=contra-ataque.it|language=Italian|author1=Claudio Agave|date=16 February 2016|accessdate=2 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Goal celebrations===\nTotti was known for his exuberant and humorous [[goal celebration]]s. One of his famous celebrations took place on 11 April 1999 in the second ''Derby della Capitale'' of the [[1998\u201399 Serie A|1998\u201399 season]], in which he scored during the final minutes of the game and celebrated by flashing a T-shirt under his jersey, which read ''\"Vi ho purgato ancora\"'' (\"I've purged you guys again\"), in reference to events at the previous derby against Lazio on 29 November 1998 when Totti helped Roma come back from 3\u20131 down with an assist to [[Eusebio Di Francesco]] for 3\u20132 and finally a goal of his own for 3\u20133.<ref name=\"roma.repubblica.it\">{{cite news|title=Dal \"Sei unica\" al selfie, tutte le esultanze di capitan Totti nei derby|trans-title=From \"you're one of a kind\" to a selfie, all of captain Totti's goal celebrations in the Rome derby matches|url=http://roma.repubblica.it/cronaca/2015/01/12/foto/dal_sei_unica_al_selfie_tutte_le_esultanze_di_capitan_totti-104794789/1/#1|work=la Repubblica|accessdate=4 May 2015|language=Italian|date=12 January 2015}}</ref> Another derby goal against Lazio saw him take over a sideline camera and aim it at the Roma fans.<ref name=\"roma.repubblica.it\" />\n\nTotti has displayed numerous T-shirts with messages on them from under his jersey over the years, including two for his wife; ''\"6 Unica\"'' (\"You're One of a kind\") and ''\"6 Sempre Unica\"'' (\"You're Still the One\"),<ref name=\"roma.repubblica.it\"/> and a political one ''\"Liberate Giuliana\"'' (\"Free Giuliana\") in honor of [[Giuliana Sgrena]], an Italian journalist kidnapped in 2005 by insurgents in Iraq who was later freed. The most recent message was ''\"Scusate il Ritardo\"'' (\"Sorry for the delay\") which he flashed on 8 January 2012 as an apology to fans for his goalscoring drought after scoring his first goal of the season versus Chievo.<ref name=\"roma.repubblica.it\"/>\n\nAs a tribute to his then-pregnant wife, [[Ilary Blasi]], Totti imitated a childbirth scene by stuffing the ball under his shirt and lying on his back while his teammates extracted the ball. His current ritual of sucking his thumb after a goal began after his son was born and continued after the birth of his daughter. Blasi has revealed that Totti also sucks his thumb in dedication to her and not just for their children.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.francescototti.com/main.html|title=Face to Face|accessdate=1 June 2012|work=Totti.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120615170114/http://www.francescototti.com/main.html|archivedate=15 June 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.footballitaliano.org/2626/tottis-goal-celebration-is-for-wife-blasi.html|title=Totti's Goal Celebration Is For Wife Blasi|date=5 January 2009|accessdate=31 May 2011|publisher=Football Italiano|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100113115443/http://www.footballitaliano.org/2626/tottis-goal-celebration-is-for-wife-blasi.html|archivedate=13 January 2010 |url-status=dead}}</ref> On 11 January 2015, Totti scored twice against Lazio in the ''Derby della Capitale'' as Roma came back from 2\u20130 down; he then took a [[selfie]] with Roma fans.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/30719796|title=Roma 2\u20132 Lazio|work=BBC Sport|date=11 January 2015|accessdate=16 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n==After retirement==\nOn 17 July 2017, Totti confirmed his retirement from professional football and announced that he had accepted an offer from his former team Roma to become a club director.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/as-roma/story/3159323/francesco-totti-confirms-retirement-and-accepts-offer-to-be-club-director-at-roma|title=Francesco Totti confirms retirement, accepts offer as club director at Roma|publisher=ESPN FC|author1=Ben Gladwell|date=17 July 2017|accessdate=17 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 September, Totti began studying for a course in order to obtain his UEFA B coaching licence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/as-roma/story/3207932/roma-director-francesco-totti-starts-uefa-b-licence-coaching-course|title=Roma director Francesco Totti starts UEFA B Licence coaching course|publisher=ESPN FC|author1=Ben Gladwell|date=19 September 2017|accessdate=21 September 2017}}</ref> However, he withdrew from the course two weeks later, as he was unable to attend the course regularly due to his commitments as a director of Roma; his former teammate Simone Perrotta took his place.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/as-roma/story/3220213/roma-director-francesco-totti-withdraws-from-coaching-course-after-two-weeks|title=Roma director Francesco Totti quits coaching course after two weeks|publisher=ESPN FC|author1=Ben Gladwell|date=4 October 2017|accessdate=5 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 June 2019, he announced his resignations from his managerial role at AS Roma, in an hour-long press conference held at the Italian Olympic Committee headquarters where he publicly accused chairman James Pallotta and the management for not involving him enough into the club's decision making, up to the point of stating he would reconsider a comeback only under a different ownership. The events marked the end for his 30-year long formal association with the club.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2019/jun/17/francesco-totti-hits-out-at-roma-hierarchy-as-he-leaves-club-after-30-years |newspaper=The Guardian |title=Francesco Totti hits out at Roma hierarchy as he leaves club after 30 years |accessdate=18 June 2019 |date=17 June 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48663777|title=Francesco Totti leaves Roma after 30 years as he resigns as director|date=17 June 2019|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=27 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Outside of professional football==\n===Personal life===\n[[File:Ilary Blasi.jpg|thumb|right|Totti's wife, [[Ilary Blasi]], in 2009]]\n\nTotti's wife, Ilary Blasi, is a former [[showgirl]] who has been a co-host of [[Italia 1]]'s hit show ''[[Le Iene]]'' since 2007. When the couple married on 19 June 2005 at the Basilica of [[Santa Maria in Aracoeli]], their wedding was aired on television with the proceeds being donated to charity. They had their first child, Cristian, on 6 November 2005. Their second child, a daughter named Chanel, was born on 13 May 2007. The couple has often been referred to as the \"Italian [[Posh and Becks|Beckhams]]\" and their private lives are often speculated upon in Italian magazines and tabloids.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lastampa.it/2009/02/06/societa/i-beckham-de-noantri-97q3FKw7MjHUJMK5VMiGmI/pagina.html|title=I Beckham de noantri|newspaper=La Stampa|language=Italian|date=6 February 2009|accessdate=12 April 2016}}</ref> On 10 March 2016, the couple gave birth to their third child, Isabel.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Serie-A/Roma/10-03-2016/totti-nata-figlia-la-terza-volta-capitano-roma-diventa-papa-140968765899.shtml|title=Totti, \u00e8 nata la figlia Isabel: il capitano della Roma \u00e8 pap\u00e0 per la terza volta|trans-title=Totti, his daughter Isabel is born: the Roma captain is a father for the third time|work=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|first=Chiara|last=Zucchelli|date=10 March 2016|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref> Totti is a [[Roman Catholic]].<ref name=\"Rome's greatest son\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Sport_Vari/Altro/11-02-2013/papa-totti-sorpreso-molto-triste-petrucci-persona-straordinaria-914250723085.shtml|title=Papa, Totti: \"Sorpreso e molto triste\" Buffon: \"Grande responsabilit\u00e0\".|work=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|date=11 February 2013|accessdate=12 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nTotti's brother Riccardo<ref name=\"Rome's greatest son\" /> serves as his agent,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.topendsports.com/athletes/football-soccer/totti-francesco.htm|title=Francesco Totti: Football (Soccer)|publisher=Topend Sports|accessdate=23 February 2017}}</ref> and manages many of his brand and business interests, under the name Number Ten, including the Francesco Totti Academy, a football training school, and the Totti Soccer School, a football camp for children with disabilities. Totti also owns a motorcycle racing team called Totti Top Sport.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/jun/19/football-star-flats-homeless-housing-francesco-totti-rome|title=The football star, the run-down flats and the sky-high rent for homeless housing|work=The Guardian|first=John|last=Hooper|date=19 June 2015|accessdate=12 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Philanthropy===\nTotti became a [[UNICEF Goodwill Ambassador#Italy|goodwill ambassador]] for [[UNICEF]] in 2003,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unicef.org/people/people_14222.html|title=Goodwill ambassadors|publisher=UNICEF|accessdate=18 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unicef.org/infobycountry/italy_francesco_totti.html|title=Francesco Totti|publisher=UNICEF|accessdate=18 June 2010}}</ref> and an ambassador for the FIFA/SOS Children's Villages in January 2006. As a fundraiser for a children's charity, he published two best-selling, self-effacing joke books containing jokes the locals often told about him and his teammates. Some of the jokes were filmed in short sketches featuring himself with good friends and national teammates Alessandro Del Piero, Gianluigi Buffon, Christian Vieri, Antonio Cassano, Marco Delvecchio, [[Alessandro Nesta]] and former national team coach Giovanni Trapattoni in a short show called ''La sai l'ultima di Totti''. On 16 January 2008, he appeared as \"PaperTotti\" in the [[Disney comics|Disney]] comic series ''[[Topolino]]''. The proceeds of the subscriptions were given to charity. The Roma captain's official testimonial was a fund raising match between singers and celebrities played on the 12 May 2008 to help raise money for the construction of the Campus Produttivo della Legalit\u00e0 e della Solidariet\u00e0 (Productive Campus of Legality and Solidarity).<ref>{{cite news|title=Maradona, Totti, Zico, Rocchi e altri fenomeni All'Olimpico la Partita del cuore|url=http://www.ilmessaggero.it/home_roma/citta/maradona_totti_zico_rocchi_e_altri_fenomeni_alolimpico_la_partita_del_cuore/notizie/24014.shtml|date=11 May 2008|accessdate=17 April 2014|work=Il Messaggero|language=Italian}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Totti helped launch a new campaign promoting Football Adopting Abandoned Children, which came about in collaboration with the Friends of Children and the Association of Italian Players. In the project, he adopted a team of around 11 young Kenyans to play football in [[Nairobi]], and then to coach them along the way.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/10/italy/2009/06/20/1335771/roma-captain-francesco-totti-to-coach-team-of-abandoned-children-|title=Roma Captain Francesco Totti To Coach Team Of Abandoned Children For Charity|publisher=Goal.com|date=20 June 2009|accessdate=3 July 2015}}</ref> In 2015, Totti and several of his teammates took to the pitch for \"Tennis with Stars\" in the [[Foro Italico]] in Rome, an event to help disadvantaged children. Tennis players such as [[Novak Djokovic]] and [[Flavia Pennetta]] participated at the event.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.repubblica.it/sport/tennis/2015/05/11/foto/djokovic_e_totti_danno_spettacolo-114139648/1/#1|title=Tennis, Internazionali: Djokovic e Totti danno spettacolo per beneficenza|work=la Repubblica|date=11 May 2015|accessdate=27 June 2015|language=Italian}}</ref> On 27 September 2016, Totti celebrated his 40th birthday live on his new [[Facebook]] page,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.us/club/as-roma/104/blog/post/2959339/roma-legend-francesco-totti-40-things-to-know-on-his-40th-birthday|title=Roma legend Francesco Totti: 40 things to know on his 40th birthday|publisher=ESPN FC|first=Terry|last=Daley|date=27 September 2016|accessdate=2 October 2016}}</ref> at the Tor Crescenza castle in Rome.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://roma.corriere.it/notizie/cronaca/16_settembre_30/quartant-anni-totti-maria-sensi-non-ci-ha-invitati-ingrato-64b17d2e-8733-11e6-b094-d674d9773420.shtml|title=Quarant'anni di Totti, Maria Sensi: \"Non ci ha invitati. Ingrato\"|work=Corriere della Sera|language=Italian|first=Maria Egizia|last=Fiaschetti|date=30 September 2016|accessdate=2 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Television, cinema and publicity===\nIn 2002, [[Fiat]] principal executive [[Gianni Agnelli]], a lifelong fan and ex-president of Juventus, chose Totti to publicize the launch of the new Stilo instead of a Juventus player.<ref name=\"La Repubblica\">{{cite news|title=Ma la Fiat tradisce i bianconeri Totti il testimonial della Stilo|url=http://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/2002/04/14/ma-la-fiat-tradisce-bianconeri-totti-il.html||date=14 April 2002|accessdate=16 April 2014|work=la Repubblica|language=Italian}}</ref> Having been signed to sportswear company [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]], Totti featured in Nike's \"[[Secret Tournament]]\" advertisement, directed by [[Terry Gilliam]], in the buildup to the 2002 World Cup in Korea and Japan.<ref name=\"Nike\"/> He appeared alongside luminaries including [[Ronaldo (Brazilian footballer)|Ronaldo]], [[Ronaldinho]], Lu\u00eds Figo, [[Roberto Carlos]] and [[Hidetoshi Nakata]], with former player [[Eric Cantona]] the tournament \"referee\".<ref name=\"Nike\">{{cite news |title=A lighter shoe, cooler kits, a faster ball, a Secret Tournament&nbsp;\u2013 every touch counts |url=http://www.nikebiz.com/story/stry_scorpion.shtml |work=NikeBiz |publisher=Nike |accessdate=16 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020602055510/http://www.nikebiz.com/story/stry_scorpion.shtml |archivedate=2 June 2002 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Claire |last=Cozens |title=Cantona hosts World Cup with a difference |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2002/apr/03/advertising.worldcupfootball2002?INTCMP=ILCNETTXT3487 |work=The Guardian |date=3 April 2002 |accessdate=16 February 2015 }}</ref>\n\nTotti has featured in [[EA Sports]]' [[FIFA (video game series)|''FIFA'' video game series]]; he starred on the cover of the Italian edition of ''[[FIFA 2002]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fifa 2002 & Totti|url=http://www2.raisport.rai.it/news/rubriche/giochi/200106/27/3b3a505001915/|publisher=Rai Sport|accessdate=17 March 2015|language=Italian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222104504/http://www2.raisport.rai.it/news/rubriche/giochi/200106/27/3b3a505001915/|archive-date=22 December 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> He also featured on the cover of ''[[Pro Evolution Soccer 4]]'' along with [[Thierry Henry]] and Italian referee [[Pierluigi Collina]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.totalvideogames.com/Pro-Evolution-Soccer-4/news/Konami-Sign-Henry-Totti-and-Collina-6062.html|title=Konami Sign Henry, Totti and Collina News|date=9 September 2004|accessdate=31 May 2011|publisher=totalvideogames.com|language=|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150503200655/http://www.totalvideogames.com/Pro-Evolution-Soccer-4/news/Konami-Sign-Henry-Totti-and-Collina-6062.html|archivedate=3 May 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Between 2005 and 2008, his sponsors changed to sportswear company [[Diadora]] and soft drink [[Pepsi Twist]], with a commercial filmed in the camps of Trigoria by director [[Gabriele Muccino]]. Since May 2006, he has appeared in advertisements for telephone company [[Vodafone]]. In December 2006 Totti and his wife Ilary Blasi lent their voices to an Italian dubbing of an episode of the television series ''[[The Simpsons]]'' entitled \"[[Marge and Homer Turn a Couple Play]]\", in which Totti voiced Buck Mitchell.<ref>{{cite news|title=Totti voce dei Simpson: \"Che intelligenti!\"|url=http://archiviostorico.gazzetta.it/2008/maggio/03/Totti_voce_dei_Simpson_Che_ga_10_080503024.shtml|date=3 May 2008|accessdate=30 April 2014|work=La Gazzetta dello Sport|first=Stefano|last=Boldrini|language=Italian}}</ref>\nIn 2007, he appeared in the movie ''L'allenatore nel Pallone 2'' in the role of a defense attorney. Since 2008, he has participated several times in the television program ''C'\u00e8 posta per te'', in the second series of the Italian drama ''Cesaroni'', in the reality show ''[[Grande Fratello (season 8)|Grande Fratello]] 8'' and in an episode of ''Paperissima''. In September 2008, a collection of figurines dedicated to him appeared in newsstands in the [[Lazio]] region entitled \"Francesco Totti, the captain\".<ref name=\"La Gazzetta dello Sport\">{{cite news|title=Album di figurine solo su Totti|url=http://archiviostorico.gazzetta.it/2008/settembre/19/Album_figurine_solo_Totti_ga_10_080919071.shtml|date=19 September 2008|accessdate=17 April 2014|work=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian}}</ref> In 2009, Totti sent a message of support to Iranian youths during the [[2009 Iranian presidential election protests]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ireport.cnn.com/docs/DOC-305559 |title=Top striker Francesco Totti sends greetings to Iranian youth |publisher=CNN |date=28 July 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pfdctv.com/?p=1749 |title=Totti sends a message in \"Farsi\" to Iranian Youth |publisher=Persian Football |date=12 March 2012 |access-date=13 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402100204/http://www.pfdctv.com/?p=1749 |archive-date=2 April 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In February 2010, Totti was named an ambassador for online [[poker]] company [[Party Poker]].<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.marketwired.com/press-release/legendary-signing-for-partypokerit-1122148.htm |title=Legendary Signing for PartyPoker.it! |publisher=PartyPoker.it |via=Marketwired |date=25 February 2010 |accessdate=17 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2010, Totti appeared alongside actor [[Russell Crowe]] in Rome to promote the special edition of the film ''[[Gladiator (2000 film)|Gladiator]]'', celebrating the tenth year of the film's release.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2010/05/15/ozasp-soccer-italy-roma-ranieri-idAFJOE64E03T20100515|title=Bored by Mourinho, Roma's gladiators fight to the end|work=Reuters|date=15 May 2010|accessdate=6 October 2015}}</ref> In December 2014, two murals of Totti, sponsored by Nike, were created in Rome.<ref>{{cite web|title=Roma, mega murales di Totti su una scuola a S. Giovanni|url=http://www.tgcom24.mediaset.it/sport/2014/notizia/roma-mega-murales-di-totti-su-una-scuola-a-s-giovanni_2026170.shtml|date=10 February 2014|accessdate=10 June 2014|publisher=Tgcom24|language=Italian}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Ancora un murales per Totti: il Capitano sulla facciata dell'ex deposito di Piazza Ragusa|url=http://www.romatoday.it/sport/murales-totti-piazza-ragusa.html|date=28 May 2014|accessdate=10 June 2014|work=RomaToday|language=Italian}}</ref> In 2014, the Swiss artist David Diehl painted Totti as one of 16 football icons most beloved by their fans.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.forza27.com/football-icons-paintings-by-david-diehl/|title=Football Icons&nbsp;\u2013 Paintings by David Diehl|publisher=Forza27|date=20 October 2014|accessdate=27 June 2015|language=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rainews.it/dl/rainews/media/Calciatori-o-icone-il-football-come-religione-d9c141fe-6328-463e-a82f-c3a7d8567a06.html|title=Totti santo subito. Calciatori icona, il football come religione|publisher=Rai News|language=Italian|accessdate=27 June 2015}}</ref> In 2015, ''[[France Football]]'' rated him one of the ten best footballers in the world over the age of 36.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.francefootball.fr/news/Le-top-10-des-meilleurs-vieux/559763|title=Le top 10 des meilleurs vieux|trans-title=The top 10 of the best oldies|publisher=France Football|language=French|first=Thomas|last=Simon|date=19 May 2015|accessdate=4 August 2015}}</ref> In 2015, Totti's famous [[Goal celebration#Memorable celebrations|selfie goal celebration]] was included amongst the goal celebrations available for ''[[FIFA 16]]'' and ''[[Pro Evolution Soccer 2016]]''; he also took a selfie in the official trailer of the video game on [[YouTube]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.forzaroma.info/news-as-roma/esultanza-selfie-totti-dopo-pes-fifa-16-annuncia/|title=Esultanza \"Selfie di Totti\", dopo PES anche FIFA 16 lo annuncia|publisher=ForzaRoma.info|date=19 June 2015|accessdate=18 August 2015|language=Italian}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/row-zed/ultra-realistic-neymar-totti-selfie-5861936|title=Ultra realistic Neymar and Totti selfie celebration: New PES trailer looks AWESOME|work=[[Daily Mirror]]|date=11 June 2015|accessdate=18 August 2015}}</ref> On 1 August 2017, a rocket carrying Totti's number 10 shirt from his final game with Roma against Genoa was launched into space from [[French Guiana]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/40801467|title=Francesco Totti: Roma legend's final shirt launched into space|work=BBC Sport|date=2 August 2017|accessdate=2 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n:Source:<ref name=\"ASROMA-Profile\" />\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width: 100pt\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|National Cup<sup>1</sup>\n!colspan=\"2\"|Continental<sup>2</sup>\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other<sup>3</sup>\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"25\"|[[A.S. Roma|Roma]]\n|[[1992\u201393 A.S. Roma season|1992\u201393]]\n|[[Serie A]]\n|2||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||2||0\n|-\n|[[1993\u201394 A